            "text": "{\"hits\":{\"hits\":[{\"id\":1735925,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:29:16.888856+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735925\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0002943\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental Particle Physics\",\"description\":\"The Department of Physics at the University of Virginia invites applicants for a Research Associate position to work on the approved Mu2e experiments at Fermilab and the proposed LDMX experiment. &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;<br> We are currently playing a leading role on the Mu2e experiment, where we are responsible for fabrication of the cosmic ray veto subsystem. We are also making important contributions to LDMX (potentially located at SLAC), a novel proposed experiment with unprecedented sensitivity to light dark matter. &nbsp;&nbsp;The group is also active in the NOvA experiment and made significant contributions to the fabrication of the NOVA detector.&nbsp; The Intensity Frontier effort at Virginia comprises two faculty, one research scientist, two postdoctoral researchers, and four graduate students, working under Professors Craig Dukes and Craig Group.<br> &nbsp;<br> A PhD in Physics is required and a PhD in Experimental High Energy Physics is strongly preferred. &nbsp;Experience with hardware, CAD software, and GEANT simulations will be considered useful skills when considering candidates. The successful candidate is expected to take leading roles in managing Mu2e fabrication and commissioning efforts for the cosmic ray veto and future UVA contributions to LDMX. Candidates are expected to be stationed in Charlottesville, but must be able to participate in substantial deployments to Fermilab and the chosen LDMX site.&nbsp;<br> &nbsp;<br> <strong>QUALIFCATION REQUIRMENTS: </strong>Candidates must have a PhD degree in Physics by the appointment start date. Strong knowledge, skills and experience in some of the following fields are required: experimental particle or nuclear physics, particle detector design, construction, or simulation. Candidates with experience in particle physics detector hardware will be preferred.<br> &nbsp;<br> <strong>APPLICATION PROCEDURE:</strong>&nbsp; Apply online at <a href=\\\"https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0002943\\\">https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0002943</a> &nbsp;and attach a cover letter, curriculum vitae, a brief statement of research interests and the contact information for three individuals who can provide professional reference letters.<br> &nbsp;<br> The position will remain open until filled.&nbsp;<br> &nbsp;<br> This is a one-year appointment; however, appointment is expected be renewed for at least an additional two, one-year increments, contingent upon available funding and satisfactory performance.<br> &nbsp;<br> For additional information about the position, please contact Craig Group (rcg6p@virginia.edu)<br> &nbsp;<br> For questions about the application process, please contact Rich Haverstrom at (rkh6j@virginia.edu).<br> <br> <em>The University of Virginia, including the UVA Health System and the University Physician&rsquo;s Group are fundamentally committed to the diversity of our faculty and staff.&nbsp; We believe diversity is excellence expressing itself through every person&#39;s perspectives and lived experiences.&nbsp; We are equal opportunity and affirmative action employers. All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to age, color, disability, gender identity, marital status, national or ethnic origin, political affiliation, race, religion, sex (including pregnancy), sexual orientation, veteran status, and family medical or genetic information.</em><br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Virginia U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903328\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-31\",\"control_number\":1735925,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522185514.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Group, Craig\",\"email\":\"rcg6p@virginia.edu\"},{\"name\":\"Haverstrom, Rich\",\"email\":\"rkh6j@virginia.edu.\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"R0002943\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735892,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:21:18.326055+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735892\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://ec.europa.eu/research/mariecurieactions/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Marie Sk\\u0142odowska-Curie Fellowships\",\"description\":\"We welcome expressions of interest from eligible researchers seeking to apply for <strong>Marie Sk\\u0142odowska-Curie Individual Fellowships </strong>&mdash; MSCA-IF 2019.<br> <br> We are looking for several researchers to join CEICO in 2020 within the MSCA funding scheme. The Central European Institute for Cosmology and Fundamental Physics (<a href=\\\"http://www.ceico.cz/\\\">http://www.ceico.cz/</a>) is a new centre within the Institute of Physics of the Czech Academy of Sciences. We are an international research group focused on the interplay between cosmology, astroparticle physics, gravity, quantum field theory, and string theory. We welcome applications in all areas related to our research. CEICO will act as the host institution, and will assist the selected candidates in preparing their own MSCA application.<br> <br> If you are interested, please apply by sending an email to <a href=\\\"mailto:ceico-jobs@fzu.cz\\\">ceico-jobs@fzu.cz</a> with a single pdf file containing your CV, a list of publications, and a half-page abstract of the research proposal by June 21, 2019 (the MSCA deadline is September 11).<br> <br> Note that, when applying with us, highly ranked proposals that will not be funded by MSCA due to budget restrictions will be automatically considered for the new H2020 Widening Fellowship. Further information about MSCA is available at <a href=\\\"http://ec.europa.eu/research/mariecurieactions/\\\">http://ec.europa.eu/research/mariecurieactions/</a>. Informal enquiries may be addressed to any member of the group.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Prague, Inst. Phys.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903135\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-21\",\"control_number\":1735892,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522155811.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Urban, Federico\",\"email\":\"federico.urban@fzu.cz\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"gr-qc\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735767,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:25.993079+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735767\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://web.infn.it/fellini/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"JUNIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"FELLINI - Fellowship\",\"description\":\"<br><strong>FELLINI&mdash;FELLOWSHIP FOR INNOVATION AT INFN (H2020-MSCA-COFUND): SELECTION PROCEDURE FOR THE RECRUITMENT OF 15 (FIFTEEN) FELLOWS</strong><br> <br> <strong>The 2nd Call for Applicants of the FELLINI programme is now OPEN until Tuesday, 16 July 2019</strong>.<br> Fifteen (15) positions as a&nbsp;<strong>researcher in physics with a 3-year fixed-term contract&nbsp;</strong>are available at INFN.<br> Applications are open to researchers of any nationality to conduct research related to the following INFN lines of research:<br> (1) Experimental Particle Physics;<br> (2) Experimental Astroparticle Physics;<br> (3) Experimental Nuclear Physics;<br> (4) Theoretical Physics;<br> (5) Technological Research.<br> <br> Candidates must have a doctoral degree or at least four years of full-time equivalent research experience and must not have resided or carried out their main activity (work, studies, etc.) in Italy for more than 12 months in the three years before the call deadline.<br> A mandatory twelve-months secondment to a different research institution or in a high-tech private company, on paid leave from INFN, is also expected.<br> <br> <strong>Employment conditions</strong>: 3-year fixed-term contract as a&nbsp;Researcher.<br> It is mandatory to start the 3-year period not later than May 2020.&nbsp;<br> <br> The&nbsp;<strong>annual total remuneration amounts to &euro; 50.520,00&nbsp;</strong>before taxes and social security and insurance withholding, including costs incurred by the INFN.<br> <br> <strong>To find out more about the FELLINI Programme:&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://web.infn.it/fellini/\\\">https://web.infn.it/fellini/</a>.&nbsp;<br> <br> To access the call and guide for applicants:&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://web.infn.it/fellini/index.php/call-and-application\\\">https://web.infn.it/fellini/index.php/call-and-application</a>.&nbsp;<br> <br> Submit your application to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://reclutamento.infn.it/ReclutamentoOnline/\\\">https://reclutamento.infn.it/ReclutamentoOnline/</a>&nbsp;by Tuesday 16 July 2019.</strong>&nbsp;<br> <br> <em>The FELLINI programme has received funding from the European Union&rsquo;s Horizon 2020 under the Marie Sk\\u0142odowska-Curie grant agreement No. 754496 (CUP I51I16000000002</em>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"INFN, Italy\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/922207\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-07-16\",\"control_number\":1735767,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522155811.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Office, FELLINI Project\",\"email\":\"fellini-office@lists.infn.it\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"cond-mat\",\"cs\",\"gr-qc\",\"hep-ex\",\"hep-lat\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\",\"math\",\"math-ph\",\"nucl-ex\",\"nucl-th\",\"physics.acc-ph\",\"physics.ins-det\",\"quant-ph\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1736228,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:29:17.031491+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1736228\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://careers.aps.org/jobs/12293157/research-associate\"}],\"ranks\":[\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Permanent Track Research Associate in LIGO Detector Characterization\",\"description\":\"Applications are invited for a Research Associate position within the Department of Physics and Astronomy at the University of British Columbia, working with Professor Jess McIver&rsquo;s group on gravitational wave astrophysics research. <p> The successful candidate will play a leading role in the characterization of the LIGO gravitational wave detectors, software infrastructure support, and data analysis efforts within the LIGO Scientific Collaboration. The ideal candidate would have strong experience and interest in gravitational wave detector characterization methods, gravitational wave data analysis, software development, and large-scale interferometer instrumentation, as well as a proven ability to lead projects within a large collaboration, and experience mentoring students and postdoctoral scholars. The position will be based at UBC, with travel to the LIGO sites as needed.</p> <p> Qualified candidates must have a PhD degree in physics, astronomy, or other related fields, and a minimum of 3 years work experience as a postdoctoral fellow or research associate at the time of the appointment.</p> <p> The University of British Columbia is located in beautiful Vancouver, Canada. Campus is less than a six hour drive from LIGO Hanford, less than five hours from the Dominion Radio Astrophysical Observatory (DRAO) and the CHIME Telescope, and a 10 minute bus ride from TRIUMF. UBC and TRIUMF are home to strong efforts in theoretical gravitational physics, astrophysics, observational astronomy, and data science.</p> <p> Interested individuals are asked to submit a cover letter, a research statement, and CV using our online application page: <a href=\\\"https://secure.phas.ubc.ca/cgi-bin/Jobs/Apply\\\">https://secure.phas.ubc.ca/cgi-bin/Jobs/Apply</a>, along with the names and contact information for at least three professional references to: <a href=\\\"mailto:jobs@physics.ubc.ca\\\">jobs@physics.ubc.ca</a>. In your research statement or cover letter, please briefly address your plans for and/or past contributions to a culture of equity and inclusion in STEM. <br><br>Applications will be reviewed starting on June 15, 2019, and will continue until position is filled.</p> <p> The expected start date of this position is August 1st, 2019. This is a three-year term appointment subject to annual renewal. Salary will be competitive, and commensurate with the qualifications and experience of the successful candidate. UBC offers Research Associates a wide ranging benefits plan that includes extended health and dental coverage, paid parental leave, and more. Research Associates are eligible to participate in the Faculty Pension Plan.</p> <p> Equity and diversity are essential to academic excellence. An open and diverse community fosters the inclusion of voices that have been underrepresented or discouraged. We encourage applications from members of groups that have been marginalized on any grounds enumerated under the B.C. Human Rights Code, including sex, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, racialization, disability, political belief, religion, marital or family status, age, and/or status as a First Nation, Metis, Inuit, or Indigenous person.</p> <p> All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however Canadians and permanent residents will be given priority.</p>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"British Columbia U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902688\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-15\",\"control_number\":1736228,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522230007.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"McIver, Jess\",\"email\":\"mciver@phas.ubc.ca\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"jobs@physics.ubc.ca\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735927,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:04:34.368206+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735927\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13778\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental Astrophysics\",\"description\":\"The Large Synoptic Survey Telescope (LSST) group at the SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory has an opening for a postdoctoral Research Associate.  <br><br> Funding is available to fill this position immediately. SLAC is leading the design, construction, integration and commissioning of the 3.2 Gigapixel Camera for the LSST. The assembly and testing of the camera is proceeding at SLAC and will continue through the end of 2020. Camera hardware commissioning and science verification at the LSST observatory then continues through the end of 2022, the start of the 10-year survey. <br><br> Our group of ~20 scientists is seeking a broad, well qualified, individual to join in building, commissioning and characterizing the LSST camera. In addition to contributing to the construction of this unique instrument, the ideal candidate would also pursue a vigorous research program relevant to the success of the camera in meeting LSST\\u2019s science goals. Thus, a successful applicant would be expected to make significant contributions early on to the commissioning and verification effort and to develop a topic for their own research in preparation for, and using, the initial data from LSST. <br><br> The LSST group is part of the Kavli Institute for Particle Astrophysics &amp; Cosmology, a joint institute of Stanford University and SLAC. SLAC is the host for the Dark Energy Science Collaboration (DESC) and SLAC group members are actively pursuing a wide range of Dark Energy research. <br><br> Note: The Research Associate role is a fixed term staff position. This is a three year fixed-term appointment with the possibility of extension. Assignment duration is contingent upon project needs and funding. <br><br> We seek a candidate with demonstrated accomplishment, a strong research background, and evidence of outstanding potential in instrumentation, experiment or observation. Candidates with a record of accomplishment in design, construction, and testing of instrumentation, including work in research areas outside of optical astronomy or cosmology, are urged to apply. <br><br> Candidates should have or be in the process of completing a Ph.D. in Physics, Astronomy or another relevant field. Applicants must provide evidence of either a recently completed PhD degree or confirmation of completion of the PhD degree requirements prior to starting the position. <br><br> Applicants should provide a curriculum vitae, publications list, a statement of research interests, and arrange for three letters of reference. SLAC and Stanford especially encourages applications from candidates who will bring diversity to the workforce in astrophysics and cosmology. All applications should be submitted through the Academic Jobs Online website at: <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13778\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13778</a>.  <br><br> Questions about this position may be directed to Professor Aaron Roodman (<a href=\\\"mailto:roodman@slac.stanford.edu\\\">roodman@slac.stanford.edu</a>).  <br><br> The review of applications will begin on June 20 2019, and will continue until the position is filled.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"SLAC\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903206\"},\"curated_relation\":true},{\"value\":\"Stanford U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/911820\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-07-31\",\"control_number\":1735927,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522195600.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Roodman, Aaron\",\"email\":\"roodman@slac.stanford.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"physics\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13778\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735924,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:26.319569+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735924\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.asc.ohio-state.edu/physics/atlas/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental High Energy Physics\",\"description\":\"The Experimental High Energy Physics ATLAS group at The Ohio State University invites applications for a postdoctoral research associate position with our group.<br><br> Our group is presently involved in several analysis and hardware projects. &nbsp;The analysis projects include &nbsp;a study of the di-Higgs production, a search for long-lived particles and searches for dark matter. &nbsp;The hardware projects include R&amp;D in radiation-hard/high-speed opto-electronics, high level trigger, and diamond detectors for the HL-LHC upgrade.<br><br> The successful candidate can be in residence at CERN or Ohio State and is expected to take a leading role in one analysis project. A candidate in residence at Ohio State&nbsp;would have the opportunity to participate in a detector R&amp;D project. <br><br>Applications should include a CV, research statement and at least 3 letters of reference sent directly to Prof. K.K. Gan,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:gan@mps.ohio-state.edu\\\">gan@mps.ohio-state.edu</a>.<br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Ohio State U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903092\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-09-01\",\"control_number\":1735924,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522185514.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Gan, K.K.\",\"email\":\"gan@mps.ohio-state.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"gan@mps.ohio-state.edu\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735919,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:26.237462+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735919\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://jobs.wm.edu/postings/35714\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Neutrino Physics\",\"description\":\"Postdoctoral Researcher in Neutrino Physics at\\u00a0William &amp; Mary<br> <br> The Experimental Particle Physics group at William &amp; Mary invites applications for a postdoctoral research associate to work the DUNE and MINERVA neutrino experiments. DUNE is a next-generation neutrino oscillation experiment, which aims to make definitive measurements of the remaining oscillation parameters. Within DUNE, the William &amp; Mary group is active in the far detector high-voltage system and anode plane assembly (APA) consortia and in the near detector effort.\\u00a0<br> <br> The MINERvA neutrino-scattering experiment has collected a rich high-statistics dataset of few-GeV neutrino and antineutrino interactions on a variety of nuclear targets. Within MINERvA, the W&amp;M group has leadership roles in analysis of the incoming neutrino flux and exclusive, inclusive, and deep inelastic scattering.\\u00a0<br> \\u00a0<br> The successful applicant will be expected to conduct research with substantial self-direction, independence, and initiative. The applicant will also be expected to take on leading roles in the construction of the DUNE detectors and in analysis and preservation of MINERvA data. Applicants are expected have a PhD in experimental particle, astro-particle, or nuclear physics by time of appointment.\\u00a0Experience in programming and data analysis or hardware development is expected.\\u00a0\\u00a0<br> <br> The appointment, which includes a benefits package, will be made for one year with the possibility of renewal up to five years, contingent on funding and annual performance review.\\u00a0<br> \\u00a0<br> Applicants must submit a cover letter, statement of research interests, and curriculum vitae at: <a href=\\\"https://jobs.wm.edu/postings/35714\\\">https://jobs.wm.edu/postings/35714</a>.\\u00a0\\u00a0<br> \\u00a0<br> You will be prompted to submit on-line the names and email addresses of three references who will be contacted by the system with instructions on how to submit letters of reference.\\u00a0<br><br>Review of applications will start July 1, 2019. Applications received after the review date may be considered, if needed.\\u00a0<br> <br> William &amp; Mary and the Department of Physics value diversity (<a href=\\\"http://bit.ly/physicsvalues\\\">bit.ly/physicsvalues</a>) and invite applications from underrepresented groups who will enrich the research, teaching and service missions of the university. William &amp; Mary is an Equal Opportunity/Affirmative Action employer and encourages applications from women, minorities, protected veterans, and individuals with disabilities.\\u00a0\\u00a0William &amp; Mary is committed to providing a safe campus community and conducts background checks on applicants for employment. \\u00a0<br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"William & Mary Coll.\",\"curated_relation\":false}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-08-31\",\"control_number\":1735919,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522180410.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Nelson, Jeff\",\"email\":\"jknels@wm.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"nucl-ex\",\"physics.ins-det\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"F0847W\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735912,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:26.069471+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735912\"},\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental High-Energy Physics\",\"description\":\"The Department of Physics and Astronomy at Tufts University seeks applicants for a Post-Doctoral Research Associate position in Experimental High-Energy Physics to work on the ATLAS experiment at CERN.<br><br>The group has made significant contributions to the Missing Transverse Energy Trigger and to the overall ATLAS trigger community. The group is particularly interested in&nbsp;precision measurements of the parameters of the Standard Model&nbsp;and in searches for physics beyond the Standard Model.<br> <br> The successful applicant will be expected to make significant personal contributions to the ATLAS physics analyses and to share responsibilities in aspects of the ATLAS trigger system and its upgrade, or with the Physics Modeling Group. &nbsp;Priority will be given to candidates interested in working on studies involving W/Z+jets events, however all physics interests will be considered. &nbsp;The applicant should have, or be about to gain, a Ph.D. in particle physics, and is expected to have experience of at least two years in active participation with a leading international particle physics experiment. &nbsp;The applicant should have expertise in data analysis techniques and in software systems used in high-energy physics including Unix operating systems and the C++ programming language.<br> <br> The position is available with a starting date as early as July &nbsp;1st, 2019, for a term of two years with possible extension contingent upon available funding, and with the possibility of holding the position at CERN. <br><br>Applicants should submit a curriculum vitae, a one-page statement&nbsp;describing their research interests, and should arrange for two letters of recommendation to be sent to Professor Pierre-Hugues Beauchemin at <a href=\\\"mailto:Hugo.Beauchemin@tufts.edu\\\">Hugo.Beauchemin@tufts.edu</a>. Electronic application materials and letters of reference in PDF format are preferred. <br><br><strong>Applications will be considered until the position gets filled.</strong> <br><br> Tufts University is an equal opportunity/affirmative&nbsp;action employer.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Tufts U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903295\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-15\",\"control_number\":1735912,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522160603.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Beauchemin, Hugo\",\"email\":\"hugo.beauchemin@tufts.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"hugo.beauchemin@tufts.edu\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1736229,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:26.410558+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1736229\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13788\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"South America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental Neutrino Physics\",\"description\":\"The Neutrino Physics and Astrophysics Group (GEFAN) at the University of Campinas (UNICAMP) is seeking a candidate for one postdoctoral position. The candidate may preferably have experience in the following fields: <br><br> Data analysis and MC simulation; <br><br> Liquid argon technology for neutrino physics; <br><br> Scintillation light detection and collection in liquid argon. <br><br> The work of the experimental neutrino group is focused on the light collection system for the DUNE far detector and it has many commitments in its design, test, and construction. The successful candidate will be initially involved in the R&amp;D for the ARAPUCA device, a novel technology for liquid argon scintillation light detection which has been designed and developed at UNICAMP and which is a candidate for the light detection system of the DUNE far detector. Good knowledge of the GEANT 4 and LArSoft packages is desirable. <br><br> The GEFAN group and the Laboratorio de Leptons have six researchers working on the neutrino physics: Ettore Segreto, Ana Machado, Orlando Peres, Marcelo Guzzo, Pedro de Holanda, and Ernesto Kemp, and several Master and Ph.D. students. The University of Campinas (UNICAMP) is a public university in the State of S\\u00e3o Paulo. It is one of the top ranking Brazilian universities as well as in Latin America. The fellowship is provided by the Funda\\u00e7\\u00e3o de Amparo \\u00e0 Pesquisa do Estado de S\\u00e3o Paulo (FAPESP) which is public funding located in S\\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil. The FAPESP postdoctoral fellowship is tax-free with an annual value of R $88,477 Brazilian reais (at the current rate, 1 US dollar is approximately 3.92 Brazilian Reais). Moving and installation expenses will be reimbursed, including the airfare and one additional monthly fellowship for installation. The fellowship includes a grant for travel and research expenses of R $12,274 Brazilian Reais per year. <br><br> The fellowship is for two years, with the possibility of extension up to two additional years (four years in total) depending on mutual interest. The starting date of the fellowship is August 1, 2019, however, it is negotiable. Depending on mutual agreement, up to one year of the fellowship can be spent in an institution outside Brazil. <br><br> Interested candidates should send their CV with a list of publications, research proposal and 3 letters of reference addressed to Prof. E. Segreto using the AcademicJobs service. <br><br> The deadline for application is 21st of June of 2019 and the evaluation of application starts afterward, though late applications will be considered until the position is filled.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"U. Campinas\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/1203495\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-21\",\"control_number\":1736229,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522230007.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Segreto, Ettore\",\"email\":\"segreto@ifi.unicamp.br\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13788\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735918,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:34:40.607553+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735918\"},\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Optical Studies for Performance and Optimization of DUNE and the LZ Dark Matter Detector\",\"description\":\"This R&amp;D work focus in the study and measurement of the optical properties of materials used in the different particle physics detectors such as the LUX-ZEPLIN (LZ) dark matter experiment or the Deep Underground Neutrino Experiment (DUNE). In the case of dark matter experiments, the energy deposited by a hypothetical dark matter particle is usually very low (&lt;10 keV), requiring detectors with very low energy thresholds. To achieve this, we need to understand very well the optical properties of the detector medium and the respective surrounding surfaces to be able to select the best possible materials and describe with accuracy the light collection in the detector. This includes properties such as the reflectance of the inner surfaces, roughness which affects the reflectance, absorption, scattering length, fluorescence, etc. The successful candidate will measure some of these properties, playing a leading role in the current R&amp;D experimental work in the LIP-Coimbra laboratory.    <p> The work is part of the project funded by the Portuguese Foundation for Science and Technology (FCT). The candidate will be part of a team of experimentalists in the LZ experiment dedicated to several aspects of R&amp;D, data analysis, experiment monitoring and control. The Portuguese team associated to this project has a long and strong record of involvement in DM experiments and R&amp;D in liquid xenon detectors. </p> <p> The conditions are the following:<br> 1. Main Research Area: Physics<br> 2. Specific Research Area: Experimental Particle Physics 3. Number of fellowships: 1 </p> <p> 4. Profile: The applicant should have a recent PhD degree in physics, physics engineering or a related field. The candidate should have experience in programming and good command of English language, both oral and written. Experience with optical instrumentation, cryogenic systems, simulation tools such as GEANT4 and data&nbsp;analysis will be advantageous (but not mandatory). Preferential factor is a relevant curriculum in experimental physics.</p>    <p> 5. Place of Work: LIP Coimbra, Department of Physics of the University of Coimbra, Rua Larga, Coimbra, Portugal. </p> <p> 6. Duration: 12 months, starting in 1 July 2019, following the regulations of the FCT <a href=\\\"https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/docs/RegulationFellowships.pdf\\\">https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/docs/RegulationFellowships.pdf</a> and the internal LIP rules for fellowships. The candidate will be strongly encouraged and supported to apply for a longer term funding during this period. </p> <p> 7. Scientific Supervision: Doctor Cla\\u0301udio Silva, LIP, Department of Physics of the University of Coimbra, Portugal. </p> <p> 8. Selection and Attribution Criteria: Short-listed candidates will be invited for an interview, which may be conducted by video-conference. The selection criteria will be: candidate&#39;s curriculum vitae, its relevance to the needs of the research project and the recommendation letters (55%), and interview (45%). LIP reserves the right to not fill the vacancy open in the present call if no suitable candidate is found. </p> <p> 9. Salary: The salary will follow the reference table for FCT fellowships within Portugal. This can be found at <a href=\\\"https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/valores.phtml.en\\\">https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/valores.phtml.en</a>. </p> <p> 10. Formalization of Application: Applications must be formalized, necessarily, by submitting the following documents: curriculum vitae, a one-page statement of research interests, copy of the PhD certificate and other documents the candidate may consider relevant to his/her application, from May 20th until June 10th 2019 at 17:30h, to the email claudio@coimbra.lip.pt (c.c. bolsas@coimbra.lip.pt). Candidates should arrange for at least one letter of recommendation to be sent directly to claudio@coimbra.lip.pt. </p> <p> 11. Selection Panel: Doctor Cla\\u0301udio Silva (LIP), Professor Jose\\u0301 Pinto da Cunha (LIP), Doctor Francisco Neves (LIP). </p> <p> 12. Legislation: A fellowship contract will be celebrated according to the &ldquo;Regulations for Research Grants of the Foundation for Science and Technology&rdquo; in force, (<a href=\\\"https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/docs/RegulationFellowships.pdf\\\">https://www.fct.pt/apoios/bolsas/docs/RegulationFellowships.pdf</a>) and to the LIP Grant regulations approved by FCT, and to the Status of Scientific Research Fellow (Law no 40/2004 of 18 of August, and its successive amendments) </p>       <br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"LIP-Coimbra\",\"curated_relation\":false}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-10\",\"control_number\":1735918,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522175246.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"da Pascoal da Silva, Claudio\",\"email\":\"claudio@coimbra.lip.pt\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"hep-ex\",\"hep-lat\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\",\"physics.acc-ph\",\"physics.ins-det\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"claudio@coimbra.lip.pt\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-22\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-22T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735667,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:08:06.476549+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735667\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://emploi.cnrs.fr/Offres/CDD/UMR5822-FLOJAC-011/Default.aspx?lang=EN\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Low-Mass Dark Matter Search and Low-Energy Neutrino Physics\",\"description\":\"<strong>The MANOIR IPNL group in Lyon (France), including 2 professors, 2 associate professors and 2 CNRS research scientists, is offering a 2-year postdoctoral position</strong>.<br> \\u00a0<br> The team works jointly on the two following projects: EDELWEISS - searching for low-mass dark matter - and Ricochet - dedicated to low-energy neutrino physics. Both projects involve the development of new cryogenic detectors with low thresholds and precise measurements of both phonon and charge signals, making extensive use of the IPNL cryogenic facility.<br> \\u00a0<br> The postdoc candidate will focus mainly on the coming SubGeV phase of the EDELWEISS experiment. The candidate will work on the optimization of its reach for Dark Matter (DM) candidates from a wide range\\u00a0of BSM physics models,\\u00a0and establish realistic inputs for the expected detector performance by exploiting the data recorded with the prototype detectors that the collaboration has operated and plans to operate both at LSM and IPNL.\\u00a0<br> The postdoc candidate will also work partly on the future Ricochet experiment aiming for a percentage-level measurement of the coherent elastic neutrino-nucleus scattering (CENNS) process at low energy. For this project, the postdoc candidate will also focus on the determination of the science potential of experiment based on these same inputs.<br> \\u00a0<br> The successful candidate will be deeply involved in the evaluation of the detector performance for both EDELWEISS and Ricochet, based on collected data sets at IPNL and LSM.<br> The hired postdoc is expected to:<br> <ul> <li> First, participate to tests of prototype detectors at IPNL, in particular in the recording and exploitation of the data sets. Then produce a realistic detector model for the Monte Carlo simulations of its performance. The IPNL efforts are dedicated to detector R&amp;D and modeling programs dedicated to improve the heat energy threshold and background rejection capabilities for Ge cryogenic detectors.</li> <li> Second, realize phenomenological studies of the impact of such upcoming low-threshold detector performance on the physics reach for both the EDELWEISS and Ricochet projects.</li> </ul> Therefore, candidates with knowledge of astroparticle physics and detection methods, and a good experience in data analysis and geant4 simulations are encouraged to apply. An experience in the operation of cryogenics detectors is not mandatory but could be an asset. Eventually, the successful candidate is also expected to actively participate in our student mentoring and tutoring programs.<br> \\u00a0<br> <strong>Applicants (&lt; 2 years after PhD) must submit a cover letter, a CV, a research report and a publication list in a single pdf file via the <a href=\\\"http://emploi.cnrs.fr\\\">emploi.cnrs.fr</a> website following this link: <a href=\\\"https://emploi.cnrs.fr/Offres/CDD/UMR5822-FLOJAC-011/Default.aspx?lang=EN\\\">https://emploi.cnrs.fr/Offres/CDD/UMR5822-FLOJAC-011/Default.aspx?lang=EN</a></strong><br> <br> In addition, they are invited to send 2 letters of recommendation to Pr. Corinne Augier (<a href=\\\"mailto:c.augier@ipnl.in2p3.fr\\\">c.augier@ipnl.in2p3.fr</a>) and Pr. Jules Gascon (<a href=\\\"mailto:j.gascon@ipnl.in2p3.fr\\\">j.gascon@ipnl.in2p3.fr</a>). <br><br> <strong>Applications will be accepted until June 17th 2019.</strong><br><br> The anticipated starting date is September 1st 2019.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Lyon, IPN\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902974\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-17\",\"control_number\":1735667,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193210.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Augier, Corinne\",\"email\":\"augier@ipnl.in2p3.fr\"},{\"name\":\"Gascon, Jules\",\"email\":\"j.gascon@ipnl.in2p3.fr\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"augier@ipnl.in2p3.fr\",\"j.gascon@ipnl.in2p3.fr\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"UMR5822-FLOJAC-011\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735664,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:08:05.660782+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735664\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13665\"}],\"ranks\":[\"JUNIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Computational Physics:Biomedical Physics, Biophysics, Condensed Matter, and Quantum Materials\",\"description\":\"Concordia University seeks to appoint a Canada Research Chair (CRC) Tier 2, a research intensive tenure-track faculty position, in Computational Physics in one of the following sub-fields: Biomedical Physics, Biophysics, Condensed Matter, and Quantum Materials.  <br><br> We are firmly committed to the principle of inclusive excellence. We very strongly encourage members of the four federally designated groups to self-identify (women, indigenous people, people with a disability, visible minorities). The selected candidate will receive a tenure-track faculty appointment in the Department of Physics, in the Faculty of Arts and Science, and is expected to become a member of the Centre for Research in Molecular Modeling (CERMM) at Concordia. We offer a world-class and diverse academic environment, including state-of-the-art research facilities and a dynamic research community. Concordia is located in Montreal, Quebec, Canada which is a highly sought after destination by students at all levels. Both the University and our governments offer many programs to promote a productive and sustainable work-life balance.  <br><br> We are looking for excellent candidates with research experience in a subfield of computational physics such as (but not exclusively): Biomedical Physics and Imaging, Molecular and Cell Biophysics, Electro-optics of Materials, Quantum Materials. Experience, or a strong interest, in using artificial intelligence (AI) methods and multi-scale modeling in computational physics/biophysics would be an asset. The Department of Physics at Concordia has research strengths in biophysics (biomedical imaging, and molecular biophysics) and condensed matter physics (theoretical/experimental quantum materials, flexible optoelectronics, and photonics). The Centre for Research in Molecular Modeling (CERMM) has substantial research strengths in molecular modeling and simulations across the disciplines of physics, biophysics, chemistry, biochemistry, biology, chemical engineering and materials science.  <br><br> Qualified candidates will have a PhD in physics, biomedical engineering, biophysics, or a related field, and have relevant postdoctoral experience. They will also have a peered-reviewed publication record showing creativity, impact, and productivity in their field of research \\u2013 taking into consideration leaves and special situations. The selected candidate will be expected to develop a strong independent research program, supervise several graduate students, secure significant external funding, and establish collaborations with some members of the Department of Physics and CERMM, as well as with external partners. Other Concordia research centers include the PERFORM Preventive Health and Biomedical Imaging Centre, the CeNSR Center for Nanoscience Research, and the CENPARMI Center for Pattern Recognition and Machine Intelligence. The Montreal research ecosystem is very rich in possible collaborations with several major universities and centers with major strengths in biomedical physics, condensed matter, and artificial intelligence. The candidate will be expected to teach in the Department of Physics at both the graduate and undergraduate level.  <br><br> About the Canada Research Chair Program The Canada Research Chairs Program is a national strategy that invests approximately $265 million per year to attract and retain the world\\u2019s most accomplished and promising minds. The goal of the CRC program is to ensure that Canadian universities \\\"achieve the highest levels of research excellence to become world-class research centres in the global, knowledge-based economy.\\u201d CRC positions at Concordia offer an attractive salary, an annual operating research fund, reduced teaching loads, and the opportunity to apply for research infrastructure through the Canada Foundation for Innovation (CFI) John R. Evans Leaders Fund (JELF). Tier 2 CRCs are awarded for five (5) years and may be renewed. Candidates eligible for Tier 2 chair positions must be exceptional emerging scholars within ten (10) years of their highest degree at the time of nomination. Applicants who are more than ten (10) years from having earned their highest degree (and where career breaks exist, such as maternity, parental or extended sick leave, clinical training, etc.) may have their eligibility for a Tier 2 chair assessed through the program\\u2019s Tier 2 justification process. Please consult the Canada Research Chairs website for full program information, including further details on eligibility criteria. <br><br> Application and Appointment Process Subject to budgetary approval, we anticipate filling this position at the rank of Assistant Professor; appointments at the rank of Associate Professor may be considered based on previous experience. The expected start date for this position is January 1st 2020 or August 1st 2020, and applications should be received by July 30th 2019 for full consideration. Review of applications will continue until the position is filled. The selected candidate will be required to work with the Department and the Faculty to prepare the formal CRC nomination according to the CRC program guidelines. The University will submit the nomination to the CRC Secretariat at the earliest opportunity.  <br><br> Applications must consist of: a cover letter (that states if candidates are, or are not, Canadian permanent residents or citizens); a current curriculum vitae (including a description of any career interruption(s) and impact(s) thereof), copies of three (3) representative publications, a five (5) page outline of the proposed research program, a one page statement outlining their perspective on and experience with diversity and inclusion in student training, as well as a brief statement of teaching philosophy/interests (if available, attach teaching evaluations). Designated and minority group applicants are strongly encouraged to self-identify in their cover letters. Candidates must also arrange to have three (3) letters of reference submitted directly online by their Referees. <b>Applications and letters of reference must be submitted electronically via the site <a href=\\\"http://AcademicJobsOnline.org\\\">AcademicJobsOnline.org</a></b> at: <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13665\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13665</a> <br><br>  Inquiries about the position should be directed to Dr. Alexandre Champagne, Chair, Dept. of Physics ( <a href=\\\"mailto:a.champagne@concordia.ca\\\">a.champagne@concordia.ca</a>).  <br><br> Persons with disabilities who anticipate needing accommodations for any part of the application process may contact, in confidence, Nadia Hardy, Vice-Provost, Faculty Development and Inclusion at vpfdi@concordia.ca or by phone at 514.848.2424 extension 4323. <br><br> All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadian and Permanent Residents will be given priority. To comply with the Government of Canada\\u2019s reporting requirements, the University is obliged to gather information about applicants\\u2019 status as either Permanent Residents of Canada or Canadian citizens. While applicants need not identify their country of origin or current citizenship, all applications must include one of the following statements: Yes, I am a citizen or permanent resident of Canada or No, I am not a citizen or permanent resident of Canada. Concordia University is strongly committed to employment equity within its community, and to recruiting a diverse faculty and staff. The University very strongly encourages applications from all qualified individuals, including women, members of visible minorities, Indigenous persons, members of sexual minorities, persons with disabilities, and others who may contribute to diversification; candidates are invited to self-identify in their applications.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Concordia U.\",\"curated_relation\":false}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-08-01\",\"control_number\":1735664,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193210.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Champagne, Alexandre\",\"email\":\"a.champagne@concordia.ca\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13665\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735663,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T13:56:48.906736+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735663\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13679\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical / Computational Condensed Matter Physics\",\"description\":\"One postdoctoral fellow position in Theoretical/Computational Condensed Matter Physics is available in the research group of Prof. Donna Sheng.  <br><br> The position is for two years, beginning the summer of 2019, with a possible one-year extension. Candidates with experiences of studying strongly correlated systems, topological quantum materials, quantum spin liquids, and unconventional superconductivity are encouraged to apply.  <br><br> Applicants are required to have a Ph.D in physics. Experiences with developing numerical (including density matrix renormalization group, tensor network, and exact diagonalization) methods are highly preferred.  <br><br> Applicants should provide a Curriculum Vita that includes a list of publications and a statement of research interest. All application materials can be submitted through Academicjobsonline or through email, to: Professor Donna Sheng (<a href=\\\"mailto:donna.sheng@csun.edu\\\">donna.sheng@csun.edu</a>).  <br><br> Screening of applications will start immediately until the position has been filled.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Cal State, Northridge\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902709\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-07-31\",\"control_number\":1735663,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193059.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Sheng, Donna\",\"email\":\"donna.sheng@csun.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"cond-mat\",\"physics\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"donna.sheng@csun.edu\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735655,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:15.080926+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735655\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13776\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental Flavor Physics\",\"description\":\"The High Energy Physics Group at Duke University invites applications for a Postdoctoral Research Associate position. <br><br> The research activities of the HEP flavor physics group focus on the study of CKM matrix elements and new physics in semi-leptonic and radiative B decays at the Belle II experiment at KEK. The group has responsibilities in the commissioning and operation of the Belle II KL/Muon ID subsystem (KLM). Belle II has begun physics running with a goal of collecting a data sample 50 times larger than was available at Belle. The successful candidate is expected to contribute significantly to the physics program as well as support the operation of the KLM. <br><br> The associate will be expected to travel for various, and possibly extended, periods to KEK. We are looking for candidates who can make creative and important contributions to our program. A PhD in experimental particle physics or related fields is required. The initial appointment is for one year, which can commence immediately. Based on mutual satisfaction and continued funding, the possibility for extension exists for a maximum of two additional years. Applicants should submit a vita and brief statement of research interests and arrange for three letters of recommendation to be uploaded to AJO. <br><br> Applications received before July 1st will be guaranteed consideration <br><br> Questions about the position can be addressed to Anselm Vossen (<a href=\\\"mailto:anselm.vossen@duke.edu\\\">anselm.vossen@duke.edu</a>). <br><br> Duke is committed to encouraging and sustaining work and learning environments that are free from harassment and prohibited discrimination. Duke prohibits discrimination and harassment in the administration of both its employment and educational policies. Duke University is an Affirmative Action/Equal Opportunity Employer committed to providing employment opportunity without regard to an individual's age, color, disability, genetic information, gender, gender expression, gender identity, national origin, race, religion, sex, sexual orientation, or veteran status. Duke also makes good faith efforts to recruit, hire, and promote qualified women, minorities, individuals with disabilities, and veterans.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Duke U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902781\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-08-31\",\"control_number\":1735655,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193059.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Vossen, Anselm\",\"email\":\"anselm.vossen@duke.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13776\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735748,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:04:22.970887+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735748\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://www.sujobopps.com/postings/79921\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experimental Neutrino Physics\",\"description\":\"Postdoctoral Researcher - Physics<br> <br> The Physics department at Syracuse University is soliciting applications for a postdoctoral researcher who will work in the area of experimental neutrino physics using liquid argon detectors.<br><br> The primary responsibility will be to participate in the evolving&nbsp;DUNE program. The candidate will also have the opportunity to participate in ongoing experiments at Fermilab&rsquo;s&nbsp;SBN&nbsp;program of which the neutrino group is involved. The appointment will begin in Fall of 2019.<br> <br> For more information and to apply, please visit&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.sujobopps.com/postings/79921\\\">http://www.sujobopps.com/postings/79921</a><br> <br> Syracuse University is an equal opportunity/affirmative action employer with a strong commitment to equality of opportunity and a diverse work force. Women, military veterans, individuals with disabilities, and members of other traditionally underrepresented groups are encouraged to apply.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Syracuse University\",\"curated_relation\":false}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-08-31\",\"control_number\":1735748,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522155618.0\",\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"physics.acc-ph\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"074475\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735762,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:25.915954+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735762\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0006486\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Electroweak Studies in Electron-Nuclear Scattering\",\"description\":\"The Department of Physics at the University of Virginia invites applicants for a Research Associate position in the study of subatomic physics through experiments conducted at the Thomas Jefferson National Accelerator Facility. <br><br>Candidates with outstanding research potential and an interest in electroweak studies in electron-nuclear scattering are especially invited to apply. The research group is currently playing a leading role on the PREX-2, CREX and MOLLER experiments measuring parity violation in electron scattering. The successful candidate will also have the opportunity to develop an independent research effort and to participate in other aspects of the rich research program at the laboratory.<br> &nbsp;<br> A Ph.D. degree in physics is required and a focus on experimental subatomic physics is strongly preferred. Priority will be given to candidates with a track-record of excellence in subatomic physics research and experience with experimental analysis, laser optics, polarized electron beams, experimental hardware, and GEANT4 simulations.<br> &nbsp;<br> <strong>APPLICATION PROCEDURE:</strong>&nbsp; Apply online at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0006486\\\">https://uva.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/UVAJobs/job/Charlottesville-VA/Research-Associate-in-Physics_R0006486</a>&nbsp;and attach a cover letter, curriculum vitae, a brief statement of research interests and the contact information for three individuals who can provide professional reference letters.<br> &nbsp;<br> Review of applications will begin on June 1, 2019, but the position will remain open until filled.&nbsp;<br><br> This is a one-year appointment; however, appointment may be renewed for an additional two, one-year increments, contingent upon available funding and satisfactory performance.<br> &nbsp;<br> For additional information about the position, please contact Kent Paschke, Professor, p<a href=\\\"mailto:paschke@virginia.edu\\\">aschke@virginia.edu</a><br> &nbsp;<br> For questions about the application process, please contact Rich Haverstrom, Faculty Search Advisor, at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:rkh6j@virginia.edu\\\">rkh6j@virginia.edu</a><br> &nbsp;<br> For more information on the benefits available to postdoctoral associates at UVA, visit&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://postdoc.virginia.edu/\\\">https://postdoc.virginia.edu</a>and <a href=\\\"https://hr.virginia.edu/benefits\\\">https://hr.virginia.edu/benefits</a>.<br> &nbsp;<br> <em>The University of Virginia, including the UVA Health System and the University Physician&rsquo;s Group are fundamentally committed to the diversity of our faculty and staff.&nbsp; We believe diversity is excellence expressing itself through every person&#39;s perspectives and lived experiences.&nbsp; We are equal opportunity and affirmative action employers. All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to age, color, disability, gender identity, marital status, national or ethnic origin, political affiliation, race, religion, sex (including pregnancy), sexual orientation, veteran status, and family medical or genetic information.</em><br> &nbsp;<br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Virginia U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/903328\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-01\",\"control_number\":1735762,\"legacy_version\":\"20190522155811.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Paschke, Kent\",\"email\":\"paschke@virginia.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"nucl-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"R0006486\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735656,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:08:19.129814+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735656\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13721\"}],\"ranks\":[\"JUNIOR\",\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Photon Science of Particle Physics & Astrophysics\",\"description\":\"<b>SCIENCE FACULTY POSITION (Associate or Full Professor)</b> <br><br> The Photon Science Department at SLAC and Stanford University invites applications for a tenured position at the Associate or Full Professor level. The successful applicant will provide technical and intellectual leadership to the Stanford faculty with a focus on research at the frontiers of X-ray ultrafast science. This will involve engaging with Department colleagues and mentoring graduate students and postdoctoral. <br><br> The successful applicant will also direct the Science, Research and Development (SRD) Division at the Linac Coherent Light Source (LCLS). Reporting to the Associate Laboratory Director (ALD) for LCLS, the SRD Division Director will be expected to develop and execute World leading research programs at LCLS and function as a critical member of the LCLS Leadership team. The successful applicant will: <br><br> \\u2022Direct and develop a research team of scientific and technical staff, both individually and collectively.<br> \\u2022Drive the continual development of in-house scientific excellence, innovation, and adventure in our scientific and technical staff. Oversee all aspects of hiring, performance management, and staff development<br> \\u2022Lead the design, planning, and execution of the LCLS research programs. Work with the wider LCLS team and user community to: <br><br> 1) Identify prioritized research directions for LCLS that will deliver internationally leading results at a scale commensurate with the investment and ambition of our laboratory and sponsors<br> 2) Plan, commission, and exploit the identified developments<br> 3) Foster a highly collaborative, positive, respectful, and inclusive culture in all aspects of our work <br><br> The Linac Coherent Light Source (LCLS) is an internationally pre-eminent X-ray science facility, operated by Stanford University at the SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory on behalf of the Department of Energy, Office of Science. This facility provides world-leading scientific capabilities to a global user community, covering a very broad research portfolio. <br><br> This is a pivotal time for LCLS, and a rare opportunity to shape the scientific nature and direction of the facility. We are nearing completion of LCLS-II, representing more than a billion dollars of investment in a new accelerator complex that will increase the X-ray repetition rate and average power by almost 4 orders of magnitude. LCLS-II will transform our ability to observe electronic and molecular dynamics, with a new suite of end stations being designed to make optimum use of the new sources. A subsequent upgrade to enable the delivery of high energy X-rays (LCLS-II-HE) is also underway, opening up the study of rare events, transient phases, and heterogeneous systems with atomic resolution and femtosecond precision. <br><br> The successful applicant will have a Ph.D. in a scientific field strongly related to LCLS science, with at least 10 years of post-Ph.D. professional experience including: <br><br> \\u2022Extensive body of research, development, or applied work that is internationally acknowledged to have defined major advancements in research<br> \\u2022Extensive experience leading and managing scientific and technical research groups and proven ability to mentor junior staff and peers, with a strong focus on career development<br> \\u2022Substantial experience in delivering complex, multi-year technical projects<br> \\u2022Work and communicate effectively with a diverse population <br><br> <b>Please submit application materials through Academic Jobs Online. </b> <br><br> Stanford is an equal employment opportunity and affirmative action employer. All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, disability, protected veteran status, or any other characteristic protected by law. Stanford welcomes applications from all who would bring additional dimensions to the University's research, teaching and clinical missions.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Slac, LCLS\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/911143\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-07-31\",\"control_number\":1735656,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193059.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Larson, Jill\",\"email\":\"faculty@slac.stanford.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\",\"cond-mat\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13721\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735661,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:28:25.842784+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735661\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://physics.asu.edu/content/postdoctoral-research-scholar-job-12876\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Condensed Matter Theory\",\"description\":\"The Department of Physics at Arizona State University invites applications for a postdoctoral research scholar position in Condensed Matter Theory in the group of Prof. Antia Botana.  <br><br> Starting date is as early as September 1, 2019. The position is initially for one year with the possibility of renewal up to one or two more years. Preference will be given to candidates with experience and strong interests in density functional theory, strongly correlated electron systems, magnetic properties and 2D materials.  <br><br>  Requirements:<br>  1) Recent Ph.D. degree in Physics, Materials Science, Chemistry, or related fields.<br>  2) Experience and interest in scientific computing and programming, preferably in Python. <br> 3) Experience in electronic structure simulations (density functional theory).<br>  4) Excellent verbal and written communication skills in English.  <br><br> Desired Skills:<br>  1) Experience in density functional theory, strongly correlated electron systems, magnetic properties and 2D materials  <br><br> To apply, please send electronically to: <a href=\\\"https://physics.asu.edu/content/postdoctoral-research-scholar-job-12876\\\">https://physics.asu.edu/content/postdoctoral-research-scholar-job-12876 </a> the following materials: a cover letter, a CV, a publication list, and a detailed summary of research experience and interests, and names and contact information of two references. Applications should be submitted in one complete attachment.  <br><br> For more information about the position, contact Antia Botana, antia.botana@asu.edu  <br><br> The initial review of applications will begin May 29th, 2019; if not filled, applications will be reviewed every week thereafter until the search is closed. <br><br>  A background check is required for employment. Arizona State University is a VEVRAA Federal Contractor and an Equal Opportunity Affirmative Action Employer. All qualified applicants will be considered without regard to race, color, sex, religion, national origin, disability, protected veteran status, or any other basis protected by law. <a href=\\\"https://www.asu.edu/aad/manuals/acd/acd401.html\\\">https://www.asu.edu/aad/manuals/acd/acd401.html</a>. <a href=\\\"https://www.asu.edu/titleIX\\\">https://www.asu.edu/titleIX</a>.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Arizona State U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902646\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-05-29\",\"control_number\":1735661,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521193059.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Botana, Antia\",\"email\":\"antia.botana@asu.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\",\"cond-mat\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13684 / 12876\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735585,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:21:15.906348+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735585\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://ppgfsc.posgrad.ufsc.br/processo-seletivo-pnpdcapes-20192/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"South America\"],\"position\":\"Post-Doctoral Position Capes/PNPD\",\"description\":\"Fellowship by PNPD/CAPES at UFSC, Florianopolis &ndash; 2019/2  &nbsp;  The Physics Graduate Program of the Federal University of Santa Catarina &ndash; PPGFSC/UFSC, Florian&oacute;polis, announces one open postdoctoral fellowship position.<br><br> Candidates can apply in one of the following research fields: Astrophysics, Atomic and Molecular Physics, Quantum Optics and Quantum Information, Condensed Matter, Statistical Mechanics, Mathematical Physics, Quantum Field Theory and Particle Physics, and Nuclear and Hadron Physics.  &nbsp;  The fellowship is sponsored by the Programa Nacional de P&oacute;s-doutorado da Coordena&ccedil;&atilde;o de Aperfei&ccedil;oamento de Pessoal de N&iacute;vel Superior&nbsp; - PNPD/CAPES, for the period of 2 (two) years. It can be renewed annually to a maximum of 60 months and the monthly amount of the fellowship is R$ 4100.00 (four thousand one hundred reais).  &nbsp;  &nbsp;  In order to apply, the candidate should fill the online form at: <a href=\\\"http://ppgfsc.posgrad.ufsc.br/processo-seletivo-pnpdcapes-20192/\\\">http://ppgfsc.posgrad.ufsc.br/processo-seletivo-pnpdcapes-20192/</a> before the deadline of May 27th.  &nbsp;  Florianopolis location:  <a href=\\\"https://www.google.com.br/maps/@-27.6103459,-48.4844367,63800m/data=!3m1!1e3?hl=en\\\">https://www.google.com.br/maps/@-27.6103459,-48.4844367,63800m/data=!3m1!1e3?hl=en</a>  &nbsp;  For more information you can contact: <a href=\\\"mailto:emmanuel.de.oliveira@ufsc.br\\\">emmanuel.de.oliveira@ufsc.br</a>  <br>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Santa Catarina U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/904931\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-05-27\",\"control_number\":1735585,\"legacy_version\":\"20190521171848.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"de Oliveira, Emmanuel G.\",\"email\":\"emmanuel.de.oliveira@ufsc.br\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"hep-lat\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"emmanuel.de.oliveira@ufsc.br\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-21\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-21T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735520,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:05:24.596785+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735520\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13708\"}],\"ranks\":[\"JUNIOR\",\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Particle Physics\",\"description\":\"The LHC Physics Center (LPC) at Fermilab (<a href=\\\"http://lpc.fnal.gov/\\\">http://lpc.fnal.gov/</a>) seeks applications for CMS LPC Distinguished Researchers (DR), in both the Senior and Junior category. The preferred starting date for the position is January 2020, with some flexibility between November 2019 and March 2020.  <br><br>  The LPC serves primarily as a resource and physics analysis hub for several hundred physicists at US institutions in the CMS collaboration. The LPC offers a vibrant community of CMS scientists from US and overseas institutions, that play leading roles in analysis of data, in the definition and refinement of physics objects, in detector commissioning and operations, and in the design and development of the detector upgrade. There is close and frequent collaboration with the Fermilab theory community. The LPC provides outstanding computing resources and software support personnel. The proximity of the CMS Tier-1 and the CMS Remote Operations Center at Fermilab allows critical real time connections to the experiment. Fermilab technical facilities support detector instrumentation developments. The LPC also offers educational workshops and tutorials in analysis techniques, software development and organizes conferences and seminar series. The DRs are an integral part of the organization and are leading activities at the LPC. For a full range of LPC activities please refer to: <a href=\\\"http://lpc.fnal.gov\\\">http://lpc.fnal.gov</a>  <br><br> We are looking for CMS members from across the collaboration with a Ph.D. in particle physics and an established track record of expertise in specific areas of high energy physics. A typical Senior DR will have had experience organizing and leading a group of physicists within CMS or another HEP experiment, or has demonstrated the potential to do so. The Junior DR program provides an outstanding opportunity for young scientists to develop an independent research program. DRs will have access to the resources available at the LPC to make major contributions to CMS in the areas of physics analysis, object identification development, detector operations, or detector instrumentation development.  <br><br> Successful candidates will ordinarily be resident at the LPC for 50% or more of their time as DR. Visiting post docs and faculty will receive up to 50% remuneration with the remainder provided by the home institution. The remuneration will be limited to salary and fringe benefits; university overhead will not be paid. DRs also receive a modest travel budget to enable regular trips to CERN, the LPC, and to conferences to present work. Each position is tenable for a minimum of six months and a maximum of one year, in the first instance. Renewal is possible but requires a new proposal. The maximum amount of time as CMS LPC DR is two years.  <br><br> Applications consist of a CV, a cover letter, a research proposal, and a plan for residency at (or travel to) the LPC. Junior DR applications require, in addition, at least three letters of recommendation. The research plan should highlight the impact which the proposal is expected have on CMS and to connect it with activities already taking place at the LPC, or with the intent to start a new program that will enhance the LPC contributions to CMS. In the cover letter, please specify the requested start and end dates, the plan for residency at the LPC, and also provide the current salary and fringe.  <br><br>  Applications will be handled online at: <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13708\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13708 </a>  <br><br> The deadline for applications and supporting letters is Wednesday, June 19, 2019. Applications received after the deadline will not be considered. <br><br> Questions about the CMS LPC Distinguished Researchers program may be directed to the LPC coordinators:  <br><br> Cecilia Gerber (gerber@fnal.gov) and Sergo Jindariani (sergo@fnal.gov)\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Fermilab\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902796\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-19\",\"control_number\":1735520,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520195731.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Jindariani, Sergo\",\"email\":\"sergo@fnal.gov\"},{\"name\":\"Gerber, Cecilia\",\"email\":\"gerber@fnal.gov\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-20\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13708\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-20T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735516,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:20:55.399898+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735516\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://kau.varbi.com/en/what:job/jobID:250600/iframeEmbedded:0/where:4\"}],\"ranks\":[\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical Condensed Matter Physics\",\"description\":\"<br> The Department of Engineering and Physics within the Faculty of Health, Science and Technology invites applications for a Senior lecturer position in Theoretical Condensed Matter Physics.  <br><br> All areas of condensed matter theory will be considered, including, but not limited to materials physics, electronic structure theory, topological phases of matter, mesoscale and nanoscale physics, soft condensed matter and computational physics. The successful candidate will be expected to develop outstanding research programs and contribute significantly to the service and educational activities of the department and University. As a new member of the growing research environment in materials science, comprising at present about 25 researchers, there are good opportunities for collaboration with researchers in materials physics, in areas such as metals, semiconductors, molecular materials, and nanostructures for optoelectronic and nanomechanical applications, and you will have access to significant research infrastructure with advanced spectroscopy and scanning probe microscopy techniques at the department. <br><br> The Main Duties: \\u2022 Teaching and assessment in our physics and engineering programs, \\u2022 Create, develop and manage education and courses, \\u2022 Developing, leading and participating in research projects in condensed matter physics, including applications for research funding, \\u2022 Participate in supervision of doctoral students in the PhD programme in Physics, \\u2022 Collaborate nationally and internationally in research and education, Administrative tasks may occur. <br><br> Qualification Requirements for the Position: To be eligible for the position, a Ph.D. in Physics or a closely related field with a proven track record of scientific and professional accomplishment in condensed matter theory is required. Documented teaching expertise is required as well as a completed qualifying course in teaching in higher education or equivalent. In special circumstances, this course may be completed within two years of employment as part of the professional development commitment. A further requirement is excellent communication skills in written and spoken English. <br><br> Assessment Criteria: Special weight will be given to demonstrated excellence and expertise in: \\u2022 Independently, as well as in collaboration with others, developing and implementing research activities in condensed matter theory, in particular in any of the areas materials physics, electronic structure theory, topological phases of matter, mesoscale and nanoscale physics, soft condensed matter, and computational physics, \\u2022 Attracting research funding, \\u2022 Teaching and assessment in courses in higher education, <br><br> Considerable weight will be given to proven skills in: \\u2022 Developing, conducting and managing education activities \\u2022 Supervision of doctoral students \\u2022 Collaborating nationally and internationally in research and education, \\u2022 Cooperation and good interpersonal relations \\u2022 Cooperate with others and create a good working environment among colleagues and students <br><br> Valuable qualifications are: \\u2022 International experience, e.g post-doctoral experience <br><br> The position is full-time, non-fixed term employment with starting date in the later part of 2019 or by agreement. <br><br> You submit your application via Karlstad University\\u2019s web based recruitment tool: <a href=\\\"https://kau.varbi.com/en/what:job/jobID:250600/iframeEmbedded:0/where:4\\\">https://kau.varbi.com/en/what:job/jobID:250600/iframeEmbedded:0/where:4</a>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Karlstad U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/907429\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-08-31\",\"control_number\":1735516,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520185615.0\",\"arxiv_categories\":[\"cond-mat\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-20\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13764 / REK2019/30\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-20T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735442,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T13:58:03.979762+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735442\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.jobbnorge.no/en/available-jobs/job/170617/phd-position-in-theoretical-physics\"}],\"ranks\":[\"PHD\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical Physics\",\"description\":\"There is a vacancy for a PhD position in Theoretical Physics at the Department of Physics and Technology.<br><br> The position is for a fixed-term period of 3 years. The position is subject to financing through the project &quot;Thermalizing Jets: New Aspects of Non-Equilibrium Processes at Colliders&quot; partly financed by the Trond Mohn Foundation.<br> <br> The project will mainly deal with theoretical studies of quark-gluon dynamics in collisions of protons and heavy-ions at the LHC accelerator at CERN. In particular, focus will be put on developing real-time methods to develop our understanding of how energetic particles, so-called jets, interact with a hot and dense nuclear medium. The candidate will contribute to developing techniques within the framework of effective field theories to tackle these challenges. Special attention will also be devoted to developing phenomenological comparisons with experimental data from present and future particle colliders. The PhD candidate will have the possibility of shorter stays at international institutes, especially at CERN.<br> <ul> <li> Applicants must hold a master&#39;s degree or the equivalent in theoretical physics or must have submitted his/her master&#39;s thesis for assessment prior to the application deadline.</li> <li> Experience from theoretical particle physics is a requirement.</li> <li> Applicants must be able to work independently and in a structured manner, and demonstrate good collaborative skills.</li> <li> Applicants must be proficient in both written and oral English.</li> </ul> <p> Personal and relational qualities will be emphasized. Ambitions and potential will also count when evaluating the candidates.<br> <br> The fellowship will be for a period of 3 years. As a PhD candidate, you must participate in an approved educational programme for a PhD degree within a period of 3 years. A final plan for the implementation of the research training must be approved by the faculty within two months after you have commenced in the position. It is a condition that you satisfy the <a href=\\\"https://www.uib.no/en/matnat/52899/admission-doctoral-education-faculty-mathematics-and-natural-sciences\\\">enrolment requirements</a> for the PhD programme at the University of Bergen.<br> <br> We can offer:</p>  <ul> <li> a good and professionally challenging working environment</li> <li> salary at pay grade 51 (Code 1017/Pay range 20, alternative 9) in the state salary scale. This constitutes a gross annual salary of NOK 449&nbsp;400. Further promotions are made according to length of service in the position.</li> <li> enrolment in the Norwegian Public Service Pension Fund</li> <li> good <a href=\\\"https://www.uib.no/en/foremployees/30808/welfare\\\">welfare benefits.</a></li> </ul> Your application must include:<br>  <ul> <li> a brief account of the applicant&#39;s research interests and motivation for applying for the position</li> <li> the names and contact information for two referees. One of these should be the main advisor for the master&#39;s thesis or equivalent thesis</li> <li> CV</li> <li> transcripts and diplomas showing completion of the bachelor&#39;s and master&#39;s degrees, or official confirmation that the master&#39;s thesis has been submitted</li> <li> relevant certificates/references</li> <li> approved documentation of proficiency in English (if required, cf. <a href=\\\"https://www.uib.no/en/matnat/52899/admission-doctoral-education-faculty-mathematics-and-natural-sciences\\\">English language requirements for PhD admission</a>)</li> <li> a list of any works of a scientific nature (publication list)</li> <li> any publications in your name</li> </ul> <p> The application and appendices with certified translations into English or a Scandinavian language must be uploaded at <a href=\\\"https://www.jobbnorge.no/en/available-jobs/job/170617/phd-position-in-theoretical-physics\\\">Jobbnorge</a>.<br> <br> For further details about the position, please contact Konrad Tywoniuk, Department of Physics and Technology (<a href=\\\"mailto:konrad.tywoniuk@uib.no\\\">konrad.tywoniuk@uib.no</a>).</p>   <p> &nbsp;</p>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Bergen U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/902665\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-15\",\"control_number\":1735442,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520155148.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Tywoniuk, Konrad\",\"email\":\"konrad.tywoniuk@uib.no\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ph\",\"nucl-th\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"konrad.tywoniuk@uib.no\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-20\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-20T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735517,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T13:58:04.534264+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735517\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13739\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Grand Challenges Initiative Teaching and Research Fellows\",\"description\":\"<br> The Schmid College of Science and Technology and Dale E. and Sarah Ann Fowler School of Engineering at Chapman University invite applications for their groundbreaking postdoctoral teaching and research fellows program. <br><br>  Appointments will begin in late summer 2019 for one year with up to two-years of extension contingent on performance.  Fellows are outstanding early-career scientists who provide innovative teaching and mentorship to undergraduate students in our Grand Challenges Initiative (<a href=\\\"http://www.chapman.edu/GCI\\\">http://www.chapman.edu/GCI</a>), as well as advance independent research in collaboration with a member of the faculty. Fellows are offered a competitive salary, benefits, research support, and personalized professional development in teaching and research. <br><br> Chapman University, located in the heart of Orange County, California, is an R2 institution now ranked #5 among western universities by U.S. News and World Report, and has gained national recognition for its commitment to excellence through innovative research and teaching. Science and engineering programs at Chapman University embody our commitment to interdisciplinarity, fostering an outstanding community of teacher-scholars across a broad range of undergraduate and graduate programs. <br><br> <b>Qualifications</b> <br><br> Postdoctoral Fellows must hold a Ph.D. or an equivalent of a doctoral degree by the beginning of employment at Chapman University. The doctorate or equivalent must have been awarded within the last five years and candidate must not have exceeded five years of prior postdoctoral experience. <br><br> <b>Responsibilities</b> <br><br> Fellows are responsible for teaching foundational coursework on critical thinking in the sciences, particularly with respect to mentoring first and second-year student teams applying critical thinking to solving problems of global importance. These problems range from removing plastics from the ocean to designing low-cost and open-source hardware capable of predicting critical medical conditions. The Grand Challenges Initiative has a new maker space dedicated to helping students turn their ideas into reality. <br><br> <b>Contact Information</b> <br><br> Candidates should submit the following electronically via Academic Jobs Online: <br><br> <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13739\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13739 </a>  <br><br> \\u00b7         cover letter<br>  \\u00b7         curriculum vitae<br>  \\u00b7         teaching philosophy statement<br>  \\u00b7         research statement<br>  \\u00b7         Chapman faculty employment application<br>    \\u00b7         names and contact information for three references   <br><br>  In the cover letter, the applicant should discuss their personal motivations and goals as they pertain to serving as a teacher and mentor in the Grand Challenges Initiative. The applicant must identify a prospective faculty mentor who holds a primary appointment in Schmid College or the Fowler School of Engineering and briefly describe the topic of a conceptual, synthesis, or review paper that they would author in collaboration with their mentor. We invite candidates from the fields of biology, biochemistry, chemistry, environmental science, math, physics, food science, computational science, computer science, data analytics, electrical engineering, and computer engineering.  <br><br> File review will commence on June 17, 2019 and will continue until the position is filled. <br><br> Questions can be addressed to the program director, Dr. Greg Goldsmith: <a href=\\\"mailto:grandchallenges@chapman.edu\\\">grandchallenges@chapman.edu</a> <br><br> The university will provide visa and immigration-related support for postdoctoral fellows. Citizenship is not a selection criterion. <br><br> Successful completion of a background check is required for the final candidate. <br><br> Chapman University is an Equal Opportunity Employer committed to fostering a diverse and inclusive academic global community.  The university is dedicated to enhancing diversity and inclusion in all aspects of recruitment and employment.  All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to race, color, religion, age, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, national origin, ancestry, citizenship status, physical disability, mental disability, medical condition, military and veteran status, marital status, pregnancy, genetic information or any other characteristic protected by state or federal law.  The university is committed to achieving a diverse faculty and staff and encourages members of underrepresented groups to apply. More information on diversity and inclusion at Chapman can be found at <a href=\\\"http://www.chapman.edu/diversity/\\\">http://www.chapman.edu/diversity/</a>.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Chapman U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/911474\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-18\",\"control_number\":1735517,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520185615.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Goldsmith, Greg\",\"email\":\"grandchallenges@chapman.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\",\"cs\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-20\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13739\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-20T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735519,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T14:04:49.503585+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735519\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13741\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Superconducting Radio Frequency\",\"description\":\"SRF Group Research Associate, Cornell University CLASSE (Cornell Laboratory for Accelerator-based Sciences and Education) has an opening for a Research Associate position in the SRF (Superconducting Radio Frequency) Group.  <br><br> Located on the campus of a premier Ivy League Research University, CLASSE has a long history of excellence in various aspects of accelerator-related sciences and technology. Cornell provides an intellectually stimulating research environment with opportunities to work with undergraduate and graduate students on collaborative research. Cornell\\u2019s SRF group has strong worldwide collaborations with laboratories and industrial partners, and the successful candidate is expected to further foster these.  <br><br> Cornell\\u2019s SRF Group conducts a wide variety of fundamental SRF science and technology R&amp;D activities, and currently supports two SRF driven accelerators at CLASSE (the Cornell Electron Storage Ring CESR, and CBETA, a novel Energy-Recovery-Linac test accelerator).  <br><br> The successful candidate\\u2019s primary focus will be on the development, commissioning, operation, and optimization of RF and SRF accelerator systems, with ample opportunities for cutting-edge research and career development. In addition, the successful candidate will conduct and lead fundamental SRF research activities.  This is an initial 3-year appointment with expectation for renewal, subject to mutual satisfaction and availability of funds. Applicants should have demonstrated experience in at least one of the following areas (multiple areas will be considered definite assets): SRF cavity fabrication, preparation, cryogenic testing, and data analysis; SRF technology design, fabrication, commissioning, and operation; RF simulations and measurements; RF technology and LLRF controls for SRF accelerators. Strong written and verbal communication skills as well as the ability to work independently and in a diverse team are expected.   <br><br> This position requires a doctoral degree in physics or applied physics, and at least 4 years of experience in SRF research (including PhD research).  <br><br> Applications should be submitted at: <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13741\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/13741</a> and should include a cover letter, a CV, a list of publications, and a detailed summary of research experience and interests. Applicants must arrange to have at least three letters of recommendation uploaded, as per instructions on the academicjobsonline website.  <br><br> For information about the position, contact Dr. Matthias Liepe at MUL2@cornell.edu. <br><br> Diversity and Inclusion are a part of Cornell University\\u2019s heritage. The College of Arts and Sciences at Cornell embraces diversity and seeks candidates who will create a climate that attracts students and faculty of all races, nationalities, and genders. We strongly encourage women and underrepresented minorities to apply. Cornell University is a recognized EEO/AA employer and educator, valuing AA/EEO, Protected Veterans, and Individuals with Disabilities\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Cornell U., CLASSE\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/911093\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-11-15\",\"control_number\":1735519,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520195731.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Liepe, Matthias\",\"email\":\"MUL2@cornell.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"hep-ex\"],\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-20\",\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-13741\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-20T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}},{\"id\":1735335,\"updated\":\"2019-07-01T15:21:38.281055+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"self\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/1735335\"},\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://lpsc.in2p3.fr/index.php/en/offres-post-doc\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Measurement of the Neutron EDM with n2EDM\",\"description\":\"<b>The Research Project</b><br> We are part of an international collaboration conducting an experimental program to measure the electric dipole moment of the neutron using the ultracold neutron source at the Paul Scherrer Institut (PSI). In this framework, the research project led by the LPSC focusses on the control of systematic effects in the next generation apparatus n2EDM, in particular those related with the mercury co-magnetometer. This system is central to the experiment and is at the origin of the dominant systematics. We are developing a dedicated experimental platform at LPSC where a UV laser has been set up to investigate various aspects of the magnetometer and perform the metrology of the mercury magnetic moment.<br> <br> <b>The Laboratory</b><br> The Laboratoire de Physique Subatomique et de Cosmologie (LPSC) in Grenoble, France, is a laboratory conducting experimental and theoretical research in fundamental physics, employing about 70 researchers. It is a joint laboratory between the CNRS and Grenoble University. The UCN group, with three permanent staff members, is doing precision experiments to probe fundamental symmetries and interactions with ultracold neutrons. For this project we also benefit from the collaboration of a team from CEA Grenoble specialized in atomic magnetometry.<br> <br> <b>The Position</b><br> The position is funded via an ERC starting grant, for a duration of 2 years, with possible extension (one additional year is presently financed).<br> The candidate will be expected to<br> * Exploit the dedicated experimental platform at LPSC with the UV laser to conduct a program to measure the systematic effects related to the mercury magnetometer and realize a first metrological measurement of the magnetic moment of stable mercury isotopes.<br> * Perform Monte-Carlo simulations of the mercury spins propagating in a non-uniform magnetic field to better understand the systematics.<br> * Participate in the design, construction and test of the mercury magnetometer for n2EDM.<br> <br> <b>Experience and Qualification Required</b><br> * A PhD in experimental physics (particle, nuclear or atomic physics)<br> * Ability to work effectively and collaboratively in a team environment<br> * Skills in analysis and instrumentation<br> * Speaking French is a plus<br> <br> <b>Application</b><br> * Interested candidates should send a CV and a cover letter briefly describing their works and interests to: <a href=\\\"mailto:guillaume.pignol@lpsc.in2p3.fr\\\">guillaume.pignol@lpsc.in2p3.fr</a> and arrange for at least 2 letters of recommendation to be sent to the same email address.<br> * The review of applications will begin June 10 but will remain open until the position is filled.<br>* The starting date of the position is flexible, ideally in fall 2019.\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"U. Grenoble Alpes\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/institutions/1322046\"},\"curated_relation\":true}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-06-10\",\"control_number\":1735335,\"legacy_version\":\"20190520155148.0\",\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Pignol, Guillaume\",\"email\":\"pignol@lpsc.in2p3.fr\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"pignol@lpsc.in2p3.fr\"]},\"legacy_creation_date\":\"2019-05-19\"},\"created\":\"2019-05-19T00:00:00+00:00\",\"links\":{}}],\"total\":555},\"links\":{\"self\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/?page=1&sort=mostrecent&q=&size=25\",\"next\":\"https://qa.inspirebeta.net/api/jobs/?page=2&sort=mostrecent&q=&size=25\"},\"sort_options\":[{\"value\":\"mostrecent\",\"display\":\"Most Recent\"},{\"value\":\"deadline\",\"displ