            "size": 100087,
            "text": "{\"hits\":{\"hits\":[{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763538,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T19:48:36.890590+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503272/post-doctoral-research-associate-2-positions\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"8188abf8-168a-4e8c-905d-f1073950823e\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Research Associate Positions, Experimental Nuclear/Neutrino Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>Two postdoctoral research positions in the EXO-200/nEXO group at UMass Amherst, led by Professors Krishna Kumar and Andrea Pocar.</div><div><br></div><div>The EXO-200/nEXO program comprises various activities, carried out by two distinct collaborations representing different phases of a long-term program to measure neutrinoless double beta decay of xenon-136. EXO-200 is an experiment operating at the WIPP mine in New Mexico and producing physics results. The nEXO project is a scaled-up experiment that will extend the sensitivity reach of EXO-200 ~100-fold. nEXO is in an R&amp;D phase to perfection design choices in view of a proposal to US and international funding agencies. Both use liquid xenon Time Projection Chambers (TPCs) operated with enriched xenon (&gt;80% Xe-136).</div><div><br></div><div>The postdoc will reside at UMass Amherst where an R&amp;D laboratory in support of nEXO is operated. In the lab we measure the properties (e.g. light collection efficiency and electronic parameters) of Silicon Photo-Multipliers (SiPMs), the photon detector of choice for nEXO. An ancillary goal of the nEXO R&amp;D program at UMass is to measure optical properties at the interface of solids and liquefied xenon (less-than-ambient temperature of 170 K). The postdoc will be in charge of day-to-day operations in the UMass laboratory, including hardware upgrades to the system.</div><div><br></div><div>Prof. Pocar is also involved in the DarkSide experiment searching for particle dark matter with large liquid argon detectors and in measurements of the solar neutrino spectrum with Borexino, both housed at the Gran Sasso laboratory in Italy. Prof. Kumar runs a broad program at Jefferson Laboratory testing fundamental symmetries via precision electron scattering experiments, such as the PREX/CREX and MOLLER experiments. The successful candidates will have the opportunity to participate in some of these efforts as well.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"UMass Amherst\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/945696\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-20\",\"control_number\":1763538,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Andrea Pocar\",\"email\":\"pocar@umass.edu\"},{\"name\":\"Krishna Kumar\",\"email\":\"kkumar@umass.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"nucl-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503272/post-doctoral-research-associate-2-positions\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"andreapocar@gmail.com\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-8598-6512\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T19:48:36.734622\",\"internal_uid\":65030,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T22:39:01.554594+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763537,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T19:33:33.557907+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15439\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"b678cfb6-124a-4024-82a3-03605c35eeb2\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Nuclear Theory\",\"description\":\"<div>The Jefferson Lab Theory Center expects to have up to three postdoctoral positions beginning in the fall of 2020 to join a program of research in theoretical hadronic and nuclear physics that motivates and supports Jefferson Lab experiments at 12 GeV and beyond.</div><div><br></div><div>This includes:</div><div>* Calculation of the properties of light nuclei and their electroweak interactions;</div><div>* Studies of strong coupling QCD on the lattice and in the continuum to compute the spectrum, decays, transition form factors and multidimensional structure of hadrons;</div><div>* The application of Effective Field Theories to nuclear and hadronic properties;</div><div>* The application of QCD factorization to observables sensitive to single and multi-dimensional hadron structures (encoded in both TMDs and GPDs), and their extraction from data using QCD global analyses;</div><div>* The application of scattering theory methods to the phenomenology of multi-hadron final states relevant for the spectroscopy program at JLab and elsewhere;</div><div>* and the implication and extension of all such studies for a future Electron-Ion Collider.</div><div><br></div><div>These positions are normally for two years, but outstanding performance may allow an extension to a third year. There are established networking opportunities to interact and collaborate with researchers worldwide to bring global experience and expertise to bear on extracting definitive physics results from the JLab 12 GeV experimental program. You can find more about the Theory Center by clicking on: <a href=\\\"https://www.jlab.org/theory\\\">https://www.jlab.org/theory</a>. A strong publication record in any of the areas of interest is essential, together with a PhD in hadron or nuclear physics.</div><div><br></div><div>Applicants must upload (1) a cover letter, (2) your cv, (3) three letters of recommendations, (4) research interest, and (5) a publication list through the Academic Jobs Online post at <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15439\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15439</a> . The applicant must also apply to Jefferson Lab\\u2019s online application tracking system for Postdoctoral Research Positions at <a href=\\\"https://www.jlab.org/job-openings\\\">https://www.jlab.org/job-openings</a> under the position numbers 12100, 12101, or 12102. The deadline for applications is December 1, 2019.</div><div><br></div><div>Position Requirements&nbsp;</div><div>* A PhD in an appropriate area of theoretical physics is a prerequisite, together with a record of publications in leading journals and talks at workshops and conferences.</div><div>* Recognized research program in theoretical nuclear and/or hadron physics that overlaps with the JLab scientific program.</div><div>Mental Requirements&nbsp;</div><div>* Ability to comprehend, formulate and communicate highly abstract concepts</div><div>* Ability to express or exchange complex ideas by means of spoken and written communication</div><div>Physical Requirements&nbsp;</div><div>* Ability to get across various locations on the laboratory site and access work areas</div><div>* Visual capabilities sufficient to use computer workstations, read documents and see safety alarms</div><div>* Auditory capabilities to hear safety alarms</div><div><br></div><div>Thomas Jefferson National Accelerator Facility (Jefferson Lab) is an Equal Opportunity Employer and does not discriminate in hiring or employment on the basis of race, color, religion, ethnicity, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, ancestry, age, disability or veteran status or on any other basis prohibited by federal, state, or local law. As part of the Lab's equal employment opportunity policy, we also take affirmative action as called for by applicable laws and Executive Orders to ensure that minority group individuals, females, disabled veterans, recently separated veterans, other protected veterans, Armed Forces, and qualified disabled persons are introduced into our workforce and considered for promotional opportunities.</div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Jefferson Lab\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/904961\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-01\",\"control_number\":1763537,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Qiu, Jianwei\",\"email\":\"jqiu@jlab.org\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/992562\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"nucl-th\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-lat\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15439\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"edwards@jlab.org\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-5667-291X\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T19:33:33.413826\",\"internal_uid\":65680,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15439 / 12100\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T22:36:03.208278+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763535,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T18:34:02.540889+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"c45843b0-a90c-4513-bc00-06077a7d162a\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"CRA Postdoctoral Fellowship\",\"description\":\"<div>The&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.cra.gatech.edu/\\\">Georgia Tech Center for Relativistic Astrophysics (CRA)</a>&nbsp;invites applications for a postdoctoral fellowship position at the CRA.&nbsp;This position is expected to be independent and in support of current research at the CRA including astrophysics, cosmology, particle-astrophysics, gravitational wave astronomy, and extra-solar planets. The CRA faculty include David Ballantyne, Tamara Bogdanovi\\u0107, Laura Cadonati, Pablo Laguna, Gongjie Li, Nepomuk Otte, Deirdre Shoemaker, Ignacio Taboada, and John Wise.</div><div>The position is initially for two years, with renewal for a third year subject to performance and availability of funding.&nbsp;The expected start date is September 1, 2020.</div><div>Applicants should email to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:CRA-postdoc@lists.gatech.edu?subject=CRA%20Postdoc\\\">CRA-postdoc@lists.gatech.edu</a>&nbsp;the following documents in a single PDF file: 1) cover letter, 2) curriculum vitae including full list of publications, and 3) a brief description of research interests&nbsp;(maximum 3 pages). In addition, applicants should arrange to have three letters of reference emailed separately to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:CRA-postdoc@lists.gatech.edu\\\">CRA-postdoc@lists.gatech.edu</a>.&nbsp;Review of applications will begin on December 16, 2019 and will continue until the position is filled.</div><div><strong>Included Benefits:&nbsp;</strong></div><div>The position includes a competitive salary, benefits, research and travel funds, and access to supercomputing facilities.&nbsp;For more information about the Georgia Tech benefits package and resources see&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.ohr.gatech.edu/benefits\\\">http://www.ohr.gatech.edu/benefits</a>. We especially encourage applications from women and groups traditionally underrepresented in physics and astrophysics. Georgia Tech is an Equal Opportunity / Affirmative Action Employer.&nbsp;</div><div><strong>Related URLs:&nbsp;</strong></div><div><a href=\\\"https://cra.gatech.edu/\\\">Center for Relativistic Astrophysics</a></div><div><a href=\\\"https://postdocs.gatech.edu/new-postdocs/welcome-to-atlanta-0\\\">GT Office of Postdoctoral Services</a></div><div><strong>Application Deadline:&nbsp;</strong></div><div>Sunday, December 15, 2019</div><div><strong>Selection Deadline:&nbsp;</strong></div><div>Saturday, February 15, 2020</div><div><strong>Current Status of Position:&nbsp;</strong></div><div>Accepting Applicants</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Georgia Tech., Atlanta\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/1275302\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-15\",\"control_number\":1763535,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ignacio Taboada\",\"email\":\"itaboada@gatech.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"CRA-postdoc@lists.gatech.edu\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"itaboada@gatech.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-3509-3457\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T18:34:02.422400\",\"internal_uid\":62067,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T22:32:38.661141+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763534,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T18:24:48.480709+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15438\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"b342062a-6607-4067-acdd-be1b81034709\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Postdoctoral positions\",\"description\":\"<div>The Institute for Fundamental Physics of the Universe (IFPU, <a href=\\\"http://www.ifpu.it/\\\">www.ifpu.it/</a>), Trieste, Italy, invites applications for several postdoctoral research positions to start in the Fall of 2020. Available positions include:</div><div><br></div><ul><li>Three positions - for two years, with a possible extension to a third year - for theoretical and phenomenological research in the areas supported by the Institute: astroparticle physics, astrophysical probes of fundamental interactions, early Universe, gravitational wave astrophysics, structures in the Universe, theory and phenomenology of gravity;</li><li>One additional position - for two years - in the area of gravitation theory [gr-qc], with focus on phenomenological aspects of black holes beyond general relativity;</li><li>Two additional positions - for two years - in the area of dark matter phenomenology and theory.</li></ul><div><br></div><div>IFPU is a newly born institute, having started its activities in the academic year 2018-2019. It is a joint initiative of International School for Advanced Studies (SISSA, <a href=\\\"https://www.sissa.it/ap/\\\">www.sissa.it/ap/</a> and <a href=\\\"https://www.sissa.it/app/\\\">www.sissa.it/app/</a>), the Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics (<a href=\\\"https://www.ictp.it/research/hecap.aspx\\\">ICTP</a>), the National Institute for Astrophysics (INAF; <a href=\\\"http://www.oats.inaf.it/index.php/en/\\\">Observatory of Trieste</a>) and the National Institute for Nuclear Physics (INFN; <a href=\\\"https://www.ts.infn.it/en\\\">Trieste Section</a>). The Institute aims at hosting and promoting a vigorous and innovative multi-disciplinary research program focused on investigating the fundamental laws of Nature under a Cosmological and Astrophysical perspective. Postdocs at IFPU work in close connections with staff members from the supporting institutions - about 30 researches in total -&nbsp;and also benefit from the extended visitor and research programs the Institute is hosting. </div><div><br></div><div>Applications, via Academic Jobs Online (<a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15438\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15438</a>), should include curriculum vitae,&nbsp;research statement, publication list and three reference letters.</div><div><br></div><div>Review of applications will begin on December 12, 2019 and continue until the positions are filled.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Institute for Fundamental Physics of the Universe, Trieste, Italy\"}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-12\",\"control_number\":1763534,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ullio, Piero\",\"email\":\"director@ifpu.it\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/985264\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"hep-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15438\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"ullio@sissa.it\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-1979-1079\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T18:24:47.550475\",\"internal_uid\":65676,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15438\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T22:30:14.530209+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763505,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T15:27:52.659399+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"e6b0c725-1b7d-49af-845f-a823ffc60e56\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Positions in theoretical astroparticle physics, cosmology and particle physics\",\"description\":\"<div>The <a href=\\\"http://www.particle-theory.rwth-aachen.de\\\">Institute for Theoretical Particle Physics and Cosmology (TTK)</a> at <a href=\\\"http://www.rwth-aachen.de\\\">RWTH Aachen University</a> invites applications for several postdoctoral positions in <strong>theoretical astroparticle physics, cosmology and particle physics</strong> (at the salary level E13 TVL). The appointments are initially for two years starting in fall 2020, and may be extended subject to performance and availability of funding.</div><div><br></div><div>The postdoctoral positions will be affiliated with the research groups of Prof. Robert Harlander, Prof. Michael Kr\\u00e4mer, Prof. Julien Lesgourgues and Prof. Philipp Mertsch. Applicants should have acquired solid international-level skills in at least one of the following topics:</div><div><br></div><ul><li>for <strong>astroparticle physics:</strong> cosmic ray acceleration and transport, radiation modelling of non-thermal sources, galactic diffuse emission in microwaves and gamma-rays, dark matter indirect searches, high-energy neutrino astrophysics;</li><li>for <strong>cosmology:</strong> physics of the early universe, CMB physics, large scale structure (galaxy correlations, lensing, 21cm), particle cosmology, numerical cosmology, parameter inference, future surveys (e.g. Euclid, SKA, CORE,...);</li><li>for <strong>particle physics:</strong> precision calculations in quantum field theory, effective field theories, Higgs physics, physics beyond the Standard Model, dark matter model building and phenomenology.</li></ul><div><br></div><div>The recruited post-docs will join an active and diverse institute, currently comprising of 10 faculty members, 9 postdocs, 16 PhD students and 20 master students. The institute is part of the DFG funded Collaborative Research Center \\\"Particle physics phenomenology after the Higgs discovery\\\", the collaborative research unit \\\"The Epistemology of the LHC\\\" and the DFG Research Training Group \\\"Physics of the Heaviest Particles at the LHC\\\". There are close links with the experimental particle and astroparticle physics groups in Aachen (AMS, Auger, CMS, FACT, IceCube and MADMAX).</div><div><br></div><div>Applicants should provide a curriculum vitae, a list of publications and a brief description of their research interests (in a single pdf file). Applications should be sent to the email address:</div><div><br></div><div><a href=\\\"mailto:ttkpostdoc@physik.rwth-aachen.de\\\">ttkpostdoc@physik.rwth-aachen.de</a></div><div><br></div><div>before December 17, 2019. Please indicate the position(s) you would like to be considered for in the body of your email. In addition, the applicant should arrange for three letters of recommendation to be sent to the same address.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"RWTH Aachen U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/910724\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-17\",\"control_number\":1763505,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Philipp Mertsch\",\"email\":\"pmertsch@physik.rwth-aachen.de\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"hep-th\",\"hep-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"ttkpostdoc@physik.rwth-aachen.de\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"pmertsch@physik.rwth-aachen.de\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-2197-3421\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T15:27:52.560654\",\"internal_uid\":65672,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T16:49:08.737241+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763502,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T15:11:31.130095+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503536/postdoctoral-research-associate-physics\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"572552a3-93f8-4b59-9c68-7c8936fb4815\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Research Associate, Theoretical Particle and Nuclear Physics\",\"description\":\"<div><strong>Job Description:&nbsp;</strong>The Physics Department at the University of Massachusetts Amherst invites applications for postdoctoral research associates in theoretical high-energy and nuclear physics. The candidates will be expected to carry out research in one or more of these areas and to work with faculty members of the Amherst Center for Fundamental Interactions, including Jordy de Vries (faculty research interests can be found at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https://blogs.umass.edu/het/\\\">https://blogs.umass.edu/het/</a>). The initial appointment is for one year, with the possibility of an extension of up to two additional years, contingent on funding.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>The candidate must have a Ph.D. in Physics or related field.</div><div><br></div><div>Qualified applicants should submit a brief research statement, curriculum vitae and arrange to have three letters of recommendation through&nbsp;<strong>Page Up:</strong></div><div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div><div><a href=\\\"http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503536/postdoctoral-research-associate-physics\\\">http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503536/postdoctoral-research-associate-physics</a></div><div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div><div>Although electronic applications are preferred, materials may also be mailed to:&nbsp;&nbsp;Racquel Kirpan, Physics Department, LGRT 1126, 710 North Pleasant St., University of Massachusetts, Amherst, MA 01003.&nbsp;&nbsp;For questions or further information about the position, please contact: Jordy de Vries (<a href=\\\"mailto:jdevries@umass.edu\\\">jdevries@umass.edu</a>).</div><div><br></div><div>Applicant should apply by the priority deadline of December 9, 2019 to ensure consideration.</div><div><br></div><div>The University of Massachusetts is committed to a policy of equal opportunity without regard to race, color, religion, gender, gender identity or expression, age, sexual orientation, national origin, ancestry, disability, military status, or genetic information in employment, admission to and participation in academic programs, activities, and services and the selection of vendors who provide services or products to the University. To fulfill that policy, the University of Massachusetts is further committed to a program of affirmative action to eliminate or mitigate artificial barriers and to increase opportunities for the recruitment and advancement of qualified minorities, women, persons with disabilities, and covered veterans. It is the policy of the University of Massachusetts to comply with the applicable federal and state statues, rules, and regulations concerning equal opportunity and affirmative action.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"UMass Amherst\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/945696\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-09\",\"control_number\":1763502,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"de Vries, Jordy\",\"email\":\"jdevries@umass.edu\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/1120905\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ph\",\"nucl-th\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://careers.umass.edu/amherst/en-us/job/503536/postdoctoral-research-associate-physics\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"devries.jordy@gmail.com\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-5037-5108\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T15:11:31.025897\",\"internal_uid\":52043,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T16:35:38.949991+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763495,\"created\":\"2019-11-08T14:11:27.465920+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.topcareer.jobs/Vacancy/irc251185_10153.aspx\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"67355fb4-99af-4c2c-a5b2-8c5af6613b88\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Research Associate - T2K Project\",\"description\":\"<div><br></div><div><strong>Post Doctoral Research Associate - T2K Project</strong></div><div><strong>UKRI- STFC</strong></div><div><strong>Didcot</strong></div><div><strong>\\u00a330,782 to \\u00a333,459 (depending on skills and experience)</strong></div><div><strong>Full time</strong></div><div><strong>Fixed term \\u2013 3 Years</strong></div><div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div><div><strong>About Us</strong></div><div>The Science &amp; Technology Facilities Council is a partner organisation within UK Research and Innovation (UKRI). UKRI is a new entity that brings together nine partners to create an independent organisation with a strong voice for research and innovation, and a vision to ensure the UK maintains its world-leading position in research and innovation.&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>T2K is one of the leading neutrino oscillation experiments and located in Japan. It sends a neutrino beam from Tokai to the SuperK detector to study neutrino flavour transitions. The HyperK Experiment is the planned upgrade to this experiment using significantly increased beam intensity and a new 20x larger far detector. The experiment has a very wide physics program, but the main aim is to measure CP violating effects in the neutrino sector.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>You will work at the particle Physics Department at the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory in Oxfordshire, but close relations exist with our colleagues at the University of Oxford. You are expected to contribute to the DAQ and electronics support for the T2K near detector in Japan and the T2K data analysis. In addition, there is the opportunity to participate in the preparation of the HyperK experiment. </div><div><strong><em>&nbsp;</em></strong></div><div><strong>About the role</strong></div><div><strong>Responsibilities include</strong></div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participation in the physics analysis of the T2K experiment </div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Supporting the data acquisition system and electronics of the T2K near detector remotely and in Japan, this will involve providing training for other users and identifying and fixing problem </div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Close communication with other groups in the UK, who provide the above support</div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Analyse the data of the experiment (oscillation and cross section), especially with our colleagues in Oxford</div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participate in national and international meetings, participating in discussion, presenting own work and disseminating the work of others </div><div>\\u00b7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other comparable duties as may be required by the supervisor or Head of Department.</div><div>For questions about the position, contact Prof A. Weber (<a href=\\\"mailto:Alfons.Weber@physics.ox.ac.uk\\\">Alfons.Weber@physics.ox.ac.uk</a>).</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><strong>About you</strong></div><div>You will have a PhD in experimental particle physics or equivalent experience, experience working in large scale experiments and a willingness to work with online and DAQ systems.</div><div>It is desirable you will have a PhD in Neutrino Physics and Previous experience working with online or DAQ systems.</div><div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div><div><strong>How to Apply</strong></div><div>Applicants are required to include a cover letter outlining their suitability for this role. </div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Applications are handled by UK SBS; to apply please click the apply button. Applicants who are unable to apply online should contact us by telephone on +44 (0)1793 867000.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>The closing date for applications is 6th December 2019.</strong></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Science & Technology Facilities Council\"}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-06\",\"control_number\":1763495,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"STFC\",\"email\":\"stfc@onefixmedia.co.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.topcareer.jobs/Vacancy/irc251185_10153.aspx\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"stfc@onefixmedia.co.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-0648-9180\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-08T14:11:27.241415\",\"internal_uid\":65670,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"IRC251185\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T16:32:52.015000+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763447,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T16:45:41.167792+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://jobs.illinois.edu\"}],\"ranks\":[\"PHD\",\"JUNIOR\",\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"51e1d1be-097b-4e37-891e-595785346c99\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Experiemental High Energy Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>FACULTY POSITION</div><div><br></div><div>EXPERIMENTAL HIGH ENERGY PHYSICS</div><div><br></div><div>UNIVERSITY OF ILLINOIS AT URBANA-CHAMPAIGN</div><div><br></div><div>The Department of Physics invites applications for a full-time tenured or tenure-track faculty position in Experimental High Energy Physics, beginning as early as August 16, 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;This is an open rank search. The successful candidate is expected to have a Ph.D. or equivalent and is required to teach effectively at both the undergraduate and graduate levels, and to conduct a vigorous and significant research program.&nbsp;Senior and mid-career faculty are encouraged to apply, but all qualified candidates will be considered.&nbsp;&nbsp;For full consideration, application materials must be received by January 15, 2020.&nbsp;Please visit <a href=\\\"http://jobs.illinois.edu\\\">http://jobs.illinois.edu</a> to view the complete position announcement and application instructions.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Illinois is an EEO Employer/Vet/Disabled <a href=\\\"http://go.ilinois.edu/EEO\\\">http://go.ilinois.edu/EEO</a></div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Illinois U., Urbana (main)\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/1112663\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-15\",\"control_number\":1763447,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Marjorie Gamel\",\"email\":\"mgamel@illinois.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"mgamel@illinois.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-6645-0942\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T16:45:41.076166\",\"internal_uid\":65661,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T16:52:11.410874+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763364,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T11:09:42.307372+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://kisd.ifj.edu.pl/docs/IFJ_PAN/55.pdf\"}],\"ranks\":[\"PHD\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"b9e6600f-4741-4981-a78e-8fdb591eec87\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"PhD student fellowship\",\"description\":\"<div>The Division of Theoretical Physics at the<em> </em>Institute of Nuclear Physics Polish Academy of Sciences (INP PAS) in Krakow offers a<strong> PhD student fellowship</strong> to be supervised by Prof. Radoslaw Ryblewski starting March 1, 2020.</div><div><br></div><div>The successful candidate will collaborate with Prof. Radoslaw Ryblewski and members of his team in realization of the Polish National Science Centre (NCN) research grant entitled: <em>Description of Relativistic Heavy-Ion Collisions in the Large Baryon Density Regime</em>. The research will be carried out along the pursuit of the PhD degree in theoretical physics.</div><div><br></div><div>For more information about the group check: <a href=\\\"https://www.ifj.edu.pl/dept/no4/nz41/\\\">https://www.ifj.edu.pl/dept/no4/nz41/</a>.</div><div>___________________________________________________________________</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Requirements:</strong></div><div><br></div><div>- <a href=\\\"http://M.Sc\\\">M.Sc</a>. in physics;</div><div>- experience/interest in theory of relativistic heavy-ion collisions;</div><div>- a fair balance between analytical and programming skills;</div><div>- knowledge of computer languages (such as C/C++/Mathematica);</div><div>- good knowledge of written and spoken English;</div><div>___________________________________________________________________</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Application procedure:</strong></div><div><br></div><div><strong>Step 1: Selection of candidate for the PhD student fellowship funded by NCN.</strong></div><div><br></div><div>By <strong>Jan. 8, 2020</strong> the candidates are requested to provide the following application documents (sent by email to: Radoslaw.Ryblewski@ifj.edu.pl):</div><ul><li>cover letter;</li><li>curriculum vitae;</li><li>information on scientific achievements (list of publications, list of conference presentations, fellowships, prizes, awards, scientific stays outside the host institution - all achievements have to be documented);</li><li>copy of the <a href=\\\"http://M.Sc\\\">M.Sc</a>. diploma</li><li>copy of the <a href=\\\"http://M.Sc\\\">M.Sc</a>. mark sheet</li><li>at least one letter of recommendation</li><li>the CV should contain the following declaration: <em>Following art. 6 sec. 1 point a, of the general regulation on the protection of personal data of 27 April 2016 (Journal of Laws EU L 119 of 05/04/2016) I consent to the processing of my personal data by the Institute of Nuclear Physics H. Niewodnicza\\u0144ski PAN for the needs of current recruitment.&nbsp;</em></li></ul><div><br></div><div>By Jan. 15, 2020 a review of the applications will be completed and the selected candidate will be contacted shortly after. The results of the competition will be published at the official website of the INP PAS.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Step 2: Enrolment in PhD studies program </strong></div><div><br></div><div>At the moment of starting receiving the fellowship (tentative date is March 1, 2020) the candidate must be enrolled in the <strong>Krakow School of Interdisciplinary PhD Studies (KISD)</strong> at the Institute of Nuclear Physics Polish Academy of Sciences. The enrolment is done on the basis of the interview. The tentative date of the interview is Feb. 19, 2020. The interview will be performed in person at the INP PAS and will be connected with the oral exam on quantum mechanics (the list of questions may be found here: <a href=\\\"https://www.ifj.edu.pl/msd/en/index.php?menu=quantum_mechanics\\\">https://www.ifj.edu.pl/msd/en/index.php?menu=quantum_mechanics</a>).</div><div><br></div><div>More information on the recruitment process will be provided immediately after selection of the candidate.</div><div>___________________________________________________________________</div><div><br></div><div>Funding:</div><div><br></div><div>The student will receive a fellowship of net income <strong>4500 PLN per month for 36 months</strong>, renewed after 12 months based on mutual agreement. (Due to lower living costs in Poland compared to Western Europe, the fellowship allows for a comfortable life standard. Within the time span of the fellowship the candidate can not receive any other funds from NCN.)</div><div><br></div><div>Enrolment in the KISD PhD studies program is connected with additional fellowship <strong>~ 2000 PLN per month</strong> for the entire timespan of the studies funded by INP PAS.</div><div>___________________________________________________________________</div><div><br></div><div>Contact:</div><div><br></div><div>All queries can be sent by email to:</div><div><br></div><div>Radoslaw Ryblewski</div><div>Associate Professor of Physics</div><div>Institute of Nuclear Physics</div><div>Polish Academy of Sciences</div><div>ul. Radzikowskiego 152</div><div>PL 31-342 Krakow, Poland</div><div>Radoslaw.Ryblewski@ifj.edu.pl</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Cracow, INP\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/902756\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-08\",\"control_number\":1763364,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ryblewski, Radoslaw\",\"email\":\"Radoslaw.Ryblewski@ifj.edu.pl\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/1056485\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"nucl-th\",\"hep-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"Radoslaw.Ryblewski@ifj.edu.pl\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"Radoslaw.Ryblewski@ifj.edu.pl\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-3094-7863\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T11:09:42.013732\",\"internal_uid\":57305,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"20200108\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T14:55:58.107660+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763363,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T11:02:36.378333+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://idobendayan.wixsite.com/mysite\"}],\"ranks\":[\"PHD\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"061461a1-fc50-4e35-a1e3-6f2fcbac2ba6\",\"regions\":[\"Middle East\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>The Physics Department in Ariel University is looking for a Ph.D. candidate to work with Dr. Ido Ben-Dayan on topics related to Early Universe Physics.&nbsp;The successful candidate will investigate contemporary topics in theoretical Cosmology with Dr. Ben-Dayan and his group.  The Ph.D. is typically 4 years. Applicants must hold a <a href=\\\"http://M.Sc\\\">M.Sc</a>. degree. Applicants are requested to send their CV, and a cover letter (optional), all in one PDF file, to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:idobd@ariel.ac.il\\\">idobd@ariel.ac.il</a>, and arrange 1-2&nbsp;reference&nbsp;letters to be sent to the same e-mail address. The&nbsp;position&nbsp;is open until filled.</div><div><br></div><div>Ariel University is located in the City of Ariel in Samaria, Israel, about 38 kilometers east of Tel-Aviv. It became a University in 2012 after being a public college for 30 years. It&nbsp;is one of the fastest growing academic institutions in Israel. Our students&nbsp;represent the full spectrum of Israeli society: Jews, Arabs, and other nationalities. Ariel University has a&nbsp;program for the absorption of new immigrants.&nbsp;The Physics Department includes 24 faculty working on diverse topics  from applied physics to mathematical physics. For&nbsp;inquiries&nbsp;please e-mail&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:idobd@ariel.ac.il\\\">idobd@ariel.ac.il</a>. Applicants will be considered for the position regardless of&nbsp;nationality, religion, gender, race and disabilities.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Ariel U. Ctr., Samaria\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/911766\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-31\",\"control_number\":1763363,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ben-Dayan, Ido\",\"email\":\"idobd@ariel.ac.il\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/1057030\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"gr-qc\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"idobd@ariel.ac.il\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"ido.bendayan@gmail.com\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6292-3981\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T11:02:36.278382\",\"internal_uid\":65655,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T14:53:02.514158+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763362,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T11:00:18.123072+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://www.jobs.cam.ac.uk/job/23792/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"b4d3b243-be72-4104-9fcd-5dbc507874a9\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Research Associates in Cosmology and Gravitation (Fixed Term)\",\"description\":\"<div>Applications are invited for up to three Postdoctoral Research Associate positions in the Relativity and Gravitation Group and the Centre for Theoretical Cosmology within Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics. Up to three positions may be offered, depending on the availability of funding, for up to three years. The theoretical and computational projects of direct relevance for these posts include: advancing observational tests of inflationary predictions from large-scale structure and the CMB, especially higher-order correlators and their estimation; studying cosmological correlators generated in the primordial universe, the general rules and symmetries they must obey; developing methods for testing General Relativity using gravitational waves with a focus on using effective field theory to describe possible deviations from GR; modelling of compact binary systems involving scalar and vector fields with the goal of identifying gravitational wave signatures that distinguish these from vacuum black-hole binaries.</div><div><br></div><div>The successful candidates will work with academic staff (Barrow, Challinor, Dafermos, Davis, Fergusson, Gibbons, Pajer, Reall, Santos, Shellard, Sherwin and Sperhake) and research staff. There are close links with the HEP group in DAMTP and the Kavli Institute for Cosmology.</div><div>The positions are expected to be available from 1 April 2020, but the start date is flexible and can be delayed until October 2020. Applicants should have, or be about to obtain, a PhD in a relevant area of theoretical physics, and have an established track record of original research and experience of working in collaboration.</div><div><br></div><div>Duties will include developing and conducting individual and collaborative research objectives, proposals and projects. You will be expected to plan your own research, with guidance if required, and to assist in the preparation of funding proposal. You must be able to communicate material of a technical nature. You may be asked to assist in the supervision of student projects and development of skills, and deliver seminars relating to the research area.</div><div><br></div><div>Informal enquiries may be made to Paul Shellard (<a href=\\\"mailto:epss@damtp.cam.ac.uk\\\">epss@damtp.cam.ac.uk</a>) and James Parke (<a href=\\\"mailto:LE21227@maths.cam.ac.uk\\\">LE21227@maths.cam.ac.uk</a>)</div><div><br></div><div>Fixed-term: The funds for this post are available for 3 years in the first instance, subject to funding.</div><div><br></div><div>Applications can be made at this website: <a href=\\\"http://www.jobs.cam.ac.uk/job/23792/\\\">http://www.jobs.cam.ac.uk/job/23792/</a></div><div><br></div><div>Please indicate the contact details of three academic referees on the online application form and upload a full CV and a description of your recent research (not to exceed three pages). Applicants should indicate their areas of interest Please let your referees be aware that they will be contacted by the Mathematics HR Office Administrator to request they upload a reference for you to our Web Recruitment System; and encourage them to do so promptly. Ensure that at least one of your referees is contactable at any time during the selection process.</div><div><br></div><div>Please quote reference LE21227 on your application and in any correspondence about this vacancy.</div><div>The University actively supports equality, diversity and inclusion and encourages applications from all sections of society. We particularly welcome applications from women and/or candidates from a BME background for this vacancy as they are currently under-represented at this level in our Department.</div><div><br></div><div>The University has a responsibility to ensure that all employees are eligible to live and work in the UK.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Cambridge U., DAMTP\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/907623\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-11\",\"control_number\":1763362,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"James Parke\",\"email\":\"LE21227@maths.cam.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"gr-qc\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"jp627@cam.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6264-1773\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T11:00:17.916810\",\"internal_uid\":65656,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T14:51:31.630031+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763361,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T10:57:19.584525+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"3427a573-335f-4200-8008-0852d96d354a\",\"regions\":[\"Middle East\"],\"position\":\"Early Universe Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>The Physics Department in Ariel University is looking for a postdoctoral researcher to work with Dr. Ido Ben-Dayan on topics related to Early Universe Physics. The position is&nbsp;initially&nbsp;for 2 years, extendable to an additional year contingent&nbsp;to funding and productivity.&nbsp;Applicants must hold a Ph.D degree in Physics or Astronomy, and should have research experience in at least one of the topics: Cosmology, High Energy Physics, Particle Phenomenology or closely related field. The postdoc will join the efforts of the research group and can also pursue his own research. The group also has ties to other research groups in other institutions in Israel.&nbsp;Applicants are requested to send their CV, list of publications, a research&nbsp;statement and a cover letter (optional), all in one PDF file, to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:idobd@ariel.ac.il\\\">idobd@ariel.ac.il</a>, and arrange 3&nbsp;reference&nbsp;letters to be sent to the same e-mail address. The&nbsp;position&nbsp;is open until filled.</div><div><br></div><div>Ariel University is located in the city of Ariel in Samaria, Israel, about 38 kilometers east of Tel-Aviv. It became a University in 2012 after being a public college for 30 years. It&nbsp;is one of the fastest growing academic institutions in Israel. Our students&nbsp;represent the full spectrum of Israeli society: Jews, Arabs, and other nationalities. Ariel University has a&nbsp;program for the absorption of new immigrants.&nbsp;The Physics Department includes 24 faculty working on a diverse topics from applied physics to mathematical physics.&nbsp;Ariel University believes that the training of young scientists from abroad will contribute to&nbsp;the expansion of scientific relations between Israel and other nations, as well as foster&nbsp;mutual cooperation in the study of contemporary issues in different sectors of medical,&nbsp;biological, humanities and social science areas. For&nbsp;inquiries&nbsp;please e-mail&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:idobd@ariel.ac.il\\\">idobd@ariel.ac.il</a>. Applicants will be considered for the position regardless of&nbsp;nationality, religion, gender, race and disabilities.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Ariel U. Ctr., Samaria\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/911766\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-15\",\"control_number\":1763361,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ben-Dayan, Ido\",\"email\":\"idobd@ariel.ac.il\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/1057030\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"gr-qc\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"idobd@ariel.ac.il\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"ido.bendayan@gmail.com\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6292-3981\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T10:57:19.465690\",\"internal_uid\":65655,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T14:50:00.409365+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763360,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T10:26:47.671729+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.jobs.cam.ac.uk/job/23921/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"85d7bb55-1af8-442a-8c24-1b4e949168c1\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\",\"North America\"],\"position\":\"MAGIS-100 Research Associate/Senior Research Associate\",\"description\":\"<div>The Department of Physics, the Cavendish Laboratory, invites applications for a Research Associate to undertake research on next-generation atom interferometry experiments. These will be sensitive to ultra-light dark matter and new fundamental interactions, and will provide a pathway towards detecting gravitational waves from astrophysical sources in the mid-frequency band (several mHz to a few Hz), thereby opening a new window on the cosmos.</div><div><br></div><div>The Research Associate will be hosted by the Department of Physics, as part of the High Energy Physics group, and will undertake research on the MAGIS (Mid-band Atomic Gravitational wave Interferometric Sensor), 100 metre tall, atomic sensor based at Fermilab, near Chicago, USA. The Research Associate will also participate in the development of the UK-based AION (Atomic Interferometry Observatory Network) project.</div><div><br></div><div>The Research Associate will work on the Cambridge contributions to MAGIS, namely the readout, controls and monitoring of the interferometer, and will develop the timing and controls synchronisation with the AION project. The ultimate goal is to establish an international network and reach its ultimate sensitivity by operating the two detectors in tandem. The Research Associate will also play a key role in understanding the data coming from MAGIS and the program of early physics exploitation, such as macroscopic tests of quantum mechanics and searches for ultra-light dark matter.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Cambridge U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/902712\"}},{\"value\":\"Fermilab\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/902796\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-01\",\"control_number\":1763360,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Prof. Valerie Gibson\",\"email\":\"gibson@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"physics.ins-det\",\"physics\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"gibson@hep.phy.cam.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6661-1192\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T10:26:47.575606\",\"internal_uid\":65652,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"KA21324\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T14:47:08.259584+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763358,\"created\":\"2019-11-07T09:08:00.763735+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"e2e8cea4-9be7-450e-a5ad-b7322bd610d3\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"2 Postdoctoral positions in BSM/Particle-Astrophysics & Cosmology Theory\",\"description\":\"<div>The Theoretical Particle Physics and Cosmology Group of the Department of Physics at King's College London offers two Research Associate (Postdoc) positions funded by the UK STFC, to start in Autumn 2020.</div><div><br></div><div>One position is to research on models of new physics beyond the Standard Model, such as new scenarios for electroweak symmetry breaking and dark matter, and possible phenomenological probes in collider and non-collider experiments. This position has a duration of 3 years.</div><div><br></div><div>The other position is to carry out research on problems in particle astrophysics and cosmology, including dark matter, baryogenesis, models of inflation and possible sources of gravitational waves. This position has a duration of 2 years.</div><div><br></div><div>Successful candidates will be expected both to collaborate with existing members of the group and to lead their own research projects in these areas. We are particularly interested in candidates open to interacting with group members working on gravitational physics and applications of theoretical physics.</div><div><br></div><div>The selection process will include competency-based questions and a panel interview. Interviews are scheduled to be held in December 2019.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>To apply for these roles we require you to register and apply through the college HR system. To minimise your time spent on this procedure note that in this online interface we need only the absolute minimum information required by the system. In addition, it would be very useful if you were able to arrange at least two letters of reference and a CV/generic research statement to be sent to academic jobs online.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>To apply to the 3 year post apply to the internal job page <a href=\\\"https://my.corehr.com/pls/kingrecruit/erq_jobspec_version_4.display_form?p_company=1&amp;p_internal_external=E&amp;p_display_in_irish=N&amp;p_process_type=&amp;p_applicant_no=&amp;p_form_profile_detail=&amp;p_display_apply_ind=Y&amp;p_refresh_search=Y&amp;p_recruitment_id=023107\\\">HERE</a> and to academic jobs online <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15419\\\">HERE</a>.</div><div><br></div><div>To apply to the 2 year post apply to the internal job page <a href=\\\"https://my.corehr.com/pls/kingrecruit/erq_jobspec_version_4.display_form?p_company=1&amp;p_internal_external=E&amp;p_display_in_irish=N&amp;p_process_type=&amp;p_applicant_no=&amp;p_form_profile_detail=&amp;p_display_apply_ind=Y&amp;p_refresh_search=Y&amp;p_recruitment_id=023087\\\">HERE</a> and to academic jobs online <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15420\\\">HERE</a>.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Please note that if you plan to apply for both roles, you should be able to reuse some of your information for the second application on the college HR system.</div><div><br></div><div>For an informal discussion to find out more about the roles please contact Prof. John Ellis, <a href=\\\"mailto:john.ellis@cern.ch\\\">john.ellis@cern.ch</a>, or Prof Malcolm Fairbairn, <a href=\\\"mailto:malcolm.fairbairn@kcl.ac.uk\\\">malcolm.fairbairn@kcl.ac.uk</a>.</div><div><br></div><div>The deadline for applications is midnight UK time on 8th December 2019.</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"King's Coll. London\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/902927\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-08\",\"control_number\":1763358,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Prof. John Ellis\",\"email\":\"john.ellis@cern.ch\"},{\"name\":\"Prof. Malcolm Fairbairn\",\"email\":\"malcolm.fairbairn@kcl.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ph\",\"astro-ph\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15419\"},{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15420\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"malcolm.fairbairn@kcl.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-0566-4127\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-07T09:08:00.671626\",\"internal_uid\":65650,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-08T08:36:39.439240+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763251,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T16:51:58.883089+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://jobs.usnh.edu/postings/34612\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"600d470b-ce41-47cb-a82a-5f5249f29263\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>The High Energy Theory and Cosmology group of the University of New Hampshire has an opening for a postdoctoral researcher whose interests will be in scalar dark matter/astroparticle physics, large scale structure, early universe cosmology, or neutron star theory, with a planned start of Fall 2020 (negotiable). The researcher will be expected to work primarily with and be supervised by Professor Chanda Prescod-Weinstein, but will be welcome to collaborate with other members of the high energy theory and high energy astrophysics groups at UNH\\u2019s Department of Physics and Astronomy and the Space Science Center. The applicants should have a Ph.D. in Physics and are expected to demonstrate significant promise and a growing record of accomplishment in theoretical high energy physics, astrophysics, and/or cosmology. The appointment will be for up to three years, pending satisfactory performance in annual reviews. Each application will be given careful consideration, and applications from members of groups that are traditionally underrepresented in physics and astronomy are strongly encouraged. </div><div><br></div><div>For full consideration, applicants should submit all materials by December 26, 2019, 11:59 p.m. EST. Applicants should upload a cover letter, a CV that includes a list of publications and the names/contact information of three reference writers, and a statement of research interests and background <a href=\\\"https://jobs.usnh.edu/postings/34612\\\">here</a>. The applicant should also arrange for three reference writers to submit letters of recommendation through this same application portal.</div><div><br></div><div>The University of New Hampshire is located in Durham, NH, about 70 miles from the major research hub of Boston, which can be reached by the Amtrak train that stops just steps away from the physics and astronomy department. </div><div><br></div><div>For more information, prospective applicants are welcome to contact Prof. Chanda Prescod-Weinstein at Chanda.prescod-weinstein@unh.edu.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"UNH, Durham\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/1275298\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-26\",\"control_number\":1763251,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Chanda Prescod-Weinstein\",\"email\":\"chanda.prescod-weinstein@unh.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"hep-th\",\"hep-ph\",\"gr-qc\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://jobs.usnh.edu/postings/34612\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"chanda.prescod-weinstein@unh.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6742-4532\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T16:51:58.675946\",\"internal_uid\":63163,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T20:07:43.047730+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763250,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T16:19:22.744680+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15221\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"39571069-8889-44ff-8860-c7d75af3e818\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Postdoctoral Fellow-Data science applied to astrophysics and particle astrophysics\",\"description\":\"<div>The Arthur B. McDonald Canadian Astroparticle Physics Research Institute at Queen's University (<a href=\\\"https://mcdonaldinstitute.ca\\\">https://mcdonaldinstitute.ca</a>) invites applications for a Postdoctoral Fellow position in the application of data science to particle astrophysics and astrophysics. The successful candidate will have an interest and expertise in the use of advanced statistical techniques, such as machine learning, to model data from particle astrophysics experiments and/or observational astronomy. The position will have a specific focus on research in neutrino physics, the nature of dark matter, and multi-messenger astronomy. The successful candidate will collaborate with members of the Queen's Particle Astrophysics group and serve as a central point of contact for the coordinated implementation of data science techniques across the broad range of experiments in which the group participates. The successful candidate will also contribute to activities in the Department that are related to machine learning and data science.</div><div><br></div><div>Candidates must have completed a Ph.D. in Physics, Mathematics/Statistics or a closely related field by the start date of the appointment. Experience in applying data science techniques in particle physics or astrophysics will be considered a strong asset.</div><div><br></div><div>The original appointment will be for two years, with an anticipated start date of September 1, 2020, and the salary range shall be $50,000-$60,000, but shall be commensurate with qualifications and experience. The successful candidate will also receive a small discretionary research bursary to cover costs such as travel to conferences.</div><div><br></div><div>Applicants should apply through Academic Jobs Online (<a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15221\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15221</a>) and submit:</div><div> \\u2022\\tCover letter</div><div> \\u2022\\tStatement of research interests and experience</div><div> \\u2022\\tA CV with a list of publications</div><div> \\u2022\\t3 letters of reference</div><div><br></div><div>The University acknowledges the potential impact that legitimate career interruption can have on a record of research. If applicable, the University encourages candidates to explain within their application the impact that career interruption has had on their record.</div><div><br></div><div>Questions about the position can be addressed to Prof. Larry Widrow (widrow@queensu.ca) or Prof. Ryan Martin (ryan.martin@queensu.ca), to whom the successful candidate will report. This Postdoctoral Fellow position at Queen\\u2019s University is governed by a Collective Agreement between the University and PSAC Local 901, Unit 2, which can be found here <a href=\\\"https://www.queensu.ca/facultyrelations/psac-local-901-unit-2/collective-agreement-post-doctoral-fellows-test\\\">https://www.queensu.ca/facultyrelations/psac-local-901-unit-2/collective-agreement-post-doctoral-fellows-test</a>.</div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Queen's U., Kingston\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/903149\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-03-31\",\"control_number\":1763250,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Ryan Martin\",\"email\":\"ryan.martin@queensu.ca\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"astro-ph\",\"cs\",\"hep-ex\",\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\",\"math\",\"nucl-ex\",\"nucl-th\",\"physics\",\"physics.acc-ph\",\"quant-ph\",\"stat\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"ryan.martin@queensu.ca\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-8648-1658\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T16:19:22.598404\",\"internal_uid\":65643,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15221\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T20:09:50.072116+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763249,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T15:58:58.061021+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://careers.pageuppeople.com/968/cw/en-us/job/511673/tenuretrack-faculty-position-in-experimental-nuclear-physicsjlab-bridge-position\"}],\"ranks\":[\"JUNIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"aacecb35-c6e6-4e9c-90a1-64732c21150e\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Tenure-Track Faculty Position in Experimental Nuclear Physics/JLab Bridge Position\",\"description\":\"<div>The Department of Physics at Virginia Tech invites applications for a tenure-track assistant professor position in the area of experimental nuclear physics. The initial appointment, for a period up to five years, will be in partnership with the Thomas Jefferson National Accelerator Facility (JLab) through the bridge program. This appointment carries release time of 50% (teaching/service) for up to the first five years in order to expedite research efforts at Virginia Tech and Jefferson Lab. We are seeking an individual with a primary interest in the physics program of hadronic and nuclear physics conducted at Jefferson Lab and potentially in the future at the proposed Electron Ion Collider. The successful individual will be expected to build a strong research program that will enhance the current programs at Virginia Tech and Jefferson Lab. Work will be performed both at the Virginia Tech campus in Blacksburg, VA and at JLab in Newport News, VA and it will require occasional travel to attend conferences and meetings.&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>The Virginia Tech Physics department has existing experimental research strengths in nucleon structure physics, weak interaction physics, neutrino physics, and heavy-flavor physics.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Diversity, equity, and inclusion are core values at Virginia Tech and the College of Science. Our excellence can only be fully realized by faculty, students, and staff who share our commitment to these values. The department of Physics seeks candidates whose research, teaching or service has prepared them to contribute to our commitment to diversity and inclusion in higher education.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Applicants must have a Ph.D. in physics or a closely related field by appointment start date.&nbsp;Postdoctoral experience is preferred. The successful candidates will be expected to establish a vigorous research program, teach effectively at the undergraduate and graduate levels, continue development of scholarly activities and professional capabilities, and participate in department, college, and university governance.&nbsp;Questions regarding the position can be directed to the Search Committee at <a href=\\\"mailto:npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu\\\">npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu</a>.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Candidates should apply at <a href=\\\"http://jobs.vt.edu/\\\">http://jobs.vt.edu/</a> (#511673).&nbsp;The application package must include a cover letter, curriculum vitae with a publication list, a research statement, a brief statement of teaching philosophy, and a statement of any previous activities aimed at expanding the diversity and/or mentoring of minorities, women, or members of other underrepresented groups as well as how the applicant will further Virginia Tech\\u2019s commitment to build a culturally diverse educational environment (<a href=\\\"http://www.inclusive.vt.edu/\\\">http://www.inclusive.vt.edu/</a>). Applicants should arrange for at least three letters of recommendation to be directly emailed to <a href=\\\"mailto:npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu\\\">npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu</a>. As part of the hiring process, the successful applicant must pass a criminal background check. To ensure full consideration, complete applications should be received by December 1, 2019.&nbsp;The expected starting date is August 10, 2020.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Virginia Tech does not discriminate against employees, students, or applicants on the basis of age, color, disability, sex (including pregnancy), gender, gender identity, gender expression, genetic information, national origin, political affiliation, race, religion, sexual orientation, or veteran status, or otherwise discriminate against employees or applicants who inquire about, discuss, or disclose their compensation or the compensation of other employees or applicants, or on any other basis protected by law. For inquiries regarding non-discrimination policies, contact the Office for Equity and Accessibility at 540-231-2010 or Virginia Tech, North End Center, Suite 2300 (0318), 300 Turner St. NW, Blacksburg, VA 24061.&nbsp;Individuals with disabilities desiring accommodations in the application process should notify Mrs. Jacqueline Woodyard, Physics Department, (540) 231-7566, or call TTY 1-800-828-1120 by the application deadline.</div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Virginia Tech., Blacksburg\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/909795\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-01\",\"control_number\":1763249,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"NP search committee\",\"email\":\"npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"nucl-ex\",\"hep-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"npsearch2019@phys.vt.edu\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"mariani@vt.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-3284-4681\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T15:58:57.932842\",\"internal_uid\":59976,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"511673\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T16:02:26.202538+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763246,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T15:06:46.950161+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://my.corehr.com/pls/uoxrecruit/erq_jobspec_details_form.jobspec?p_id=143635\"}],\"ranks\":[\"SENIOR\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"78d46e91-6b18-4b17-a902-0e1cd8124927\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Associate Professor of Non-Accelerator Particle Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>Associate Professor of Non-Accelerator Particle Physics Department of Physics, Parks Road, Oxford</div><div><br></div><div>Grade 30S: \\u00a348,114 - \\u00a364,605 p.a.</div><div><br></div><div>The Department of Physics proposes to appoint an Associate Professor or Professor in Non-Accelerator Particle Physics with effect from June 2020 or as soon as possible thereafter. The successful candidate will also be offered a Tutorial Fellowship at Lincoln College, under arrangements described in the job description. The combined University and College salary will be in the range \\u00a348,114 - \\u00a364,605 p.a. plus substantial additional benefits including a College housing allowance of \\u00a39,704 p.a., access to housing loan scheme, tutor\\u2019s allowance of \\u00a35,660 p.a. and private healthcare scheme. An allowance of \\u00a32,804 p.a. would be payable upon award of Full Professor title. Full Professors also have access to further merit-based pay awards.</div><div><br></div><div>The Associate Professor will join a vigorous community of particle physicists addressing the most significant issues in our understanding of the fundamental laws of nature in and beyond the Standard Model. These challenges include the nature of dark matter, the cosmological constant problem and \\u2018dark energy\\u2019, the origin of the generations, and the stability of mass hierarchies. The purpose of this appointment is to recruit a non-accelerator experimental particle physicist who would join the LUX-ZEPLIN or SNO+ experiments in the first instance. The successful candidate would also be expected engage with the development of advanced dark matter or neutrino-less double beta detection techniques that go well beyond the current LUX-ZEPLIN or SNO+ programmes, this includes the application of quantum sensing to search for light dark matter. The postholder will work closely with other particle theorists and experimentalists in the department who are involved in many of the leading experimental collaborations.</div><div><br></div><div>The successful candidate will hold a doctorate in experimental particle physics, or a related subject, and will have a proven record of high-quality creative research in non-accelerator particle/astroparticle physics at an international level. They will be an excellent teacher at undergraduate and graduate level. They will be expected to develop a world-leading research programme addressing the fundamental challenges in our understanding of the laws of nature, to teach at undergraduate and graduate level, and to participate in administration and governance of Lincoln College and the Physics Department.</div><div><br></div><div>Further particulars, containing details of the application procedure and of the duties, may be obtained below. Enquiries may be made to Professor Hans Kraus (<a href=\\\"mailto:hans.kraus@physics.ox.ac.uk\\\">hans.kraus@physics.ox.ac.uk</a>) or Professor Daniela Bortoletto at (<a href=\\\"mailto:daniela.bortoletto@physics.ox.ac.uk\\\">daniela.bortoletto@physics.ox.ac.uk</a>). Enquiries about the college side of the appointment should be addressed to Dr Lydia Matthews (<a href=\\\"mailto:lydia.matthews@lincoln.ox.ac.uk\\\">lydia.matthews@lincoln.ox.ac.uk</a>). Applicants must be available to take up the post by 31 July 2020.</div><div>Please quote departmental reference 143635 on all correspondence. Applicants should ensure that their referees send letters by the same deadline.</div><div><br></div><div>The closing date for applications is 12.00 noon on Friday 6 December 2019. Interviews will take place the week of 27 January 2020 with an offer made soon after.</div><div>Applications are particularly welcome from women and black and minority ethnic candidates, who are under-represented in academic posts in Oxford.</div><div><br></div><div>Contact Person : Sue GeddesVacancy ID : 143635Contact Phone :</div><div>Closing Date : 06-Dec-2019Contact Email : <a href=\\\"mailto:sue.geddes@physics.ox.ac.uk?subject=Associate Professor of Non-Accelerator Particle Physics\\\">sue.geddes@physics.ox.ac.uk</a></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Oxford U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/903112\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-06\",\"control_number\":1763246,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Mrs Sue Geddes\",\"email\":\"sue.geddes@physics.ox.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"eess\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"emails\":[\"sue.geddes@physics.ox.ac.uk\"]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"sue.geddes@physics.ox.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-4172-2627\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T15:06:46.799702\",\"internal_uid\":65163,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"143635\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T15:59:02.212479+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763214,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T13:59:23.350497+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://apply.interfolio.com/64593\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"e9f9adec-5883-4a48-b18a-b77d1186a560\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"CMS experiment\",\"description\":\"<div>The Department of Physics at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) invites applications for a postdoctoral fellow position to work on the CMS experiment at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) at CERN. The current CMS group at CMU consists of Professors John Alison and Manfred Paulini as well as emeriti faculty Thomas Ferguson, James Russ, and Helmut Vogel.</div><div><br></div><div>We expect the successful applicant to significantly contribute to CMU's involvement in the CMS Phase-2 upgrade for the High-Luminosity LHC, where CMU is setting up a module assembly center for the CMS high-granularity endcap calorimeter upgrade. We are also involved in the operation of the CMS electromagnetic calorimeter. Our group is active in CMS data analyses using the Higgs boson and models of supersymmetry to search for physics beyond the standard model. We also work with faculty in CMU's departments of Machine Learning and Statistics. Applications from candidates with interests in exploring machine learning in particle physics are especially welcome.</div><div><br></div><div>A Ph.D. in experimental high energy physics at the time of appointment is required. The position is based at CMU for at least the first two years. The appointment is initially for one year and renewable annually, subject to mutual satisfaction.</div><div><br></div><div>Applications, including a curriculum vitae, publication list and a statement of research interests should be submitted to <a href=\\\"http://apply.interfolio.com/64593\\\">http://apply.interfolio.com/64593</a> . In addition, candidates should arrange for three letters of recommendation to also be uploaded to the Interfolio website above. For questions about the position, please contact Manfred Paulini at paulini@cmu.edu.</div><div><br></div><div>Carnegie Mellon University is an equal opportunity employer and considers applicants for employment without regard to, and does not discriminate on the basis of, gender, race, protected veteran status, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity, and any additional legally protected status. We are committed to increasing the diversity of our community on a range of intellectual and cultural dimensions. CMU's Department of Physics especially welcomes applicants who will contribute to this diversity through their research, teaching and service, including women, members of minority groups, protected veterans, individuals with disabilities, and others who would contribute in different ways.</div><div><br></div><div>The position is available as soon as possible but remains open until filled. Applications received by January 6, 2020 will receive full consideration.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Carnegie Mellon U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/902719\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-06\",\"control_number\":1763214,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Paulini, Manfred\",\"email\":\"paulini@cmu.edu\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/994031\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"paulini@andrew.cmu.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-6714-5787\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T13:59:23.228734\",\"internal_uid\":60150,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T15:58:28.466366+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763203,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T09:02:10.208153+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://www.hep.ucl.ac.uk/cdt-dis/studentships.shtml\"}],\"ranks\":[\"PHD\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"f0fe4d67-1b26-4b79-8949-177bf944e6c6\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"PhD studentships in particle physics and astronomy\",\"description\":\"<div>The STFC Centre for Doctoral Training (CDT) in Data Intensive Science (DIS) at UCL is welcoming applications from outstanding candidates for up to 10 4-year PhD studentships for research in DIS topics, predominantly in Astrophysics and Particle Physics, to start in the academic year 2020/21. The studentships comprise full UK/EU tuition fees and a tax-free maintenance allowance equivalent to that of standard STFC studentships (\\u00a317,009 pa in 2019/20). They also come with additional funding for travel and equipment. The deadline for applications is <strong>25 January 2020</strong>.</div><div><br></div><div>The UCL CDT in DIS is the first Centre of its kind funded by STFC. UCL has a long-standing tradition of excellence in data intensive science, with pioneering contributions and leading roles in many international projects in Particle Physics and Astronomy, as well as a strong culture of cross-disciplinary research and collaboration between academia and industry. The Centre will build on these strengths to train the next generation of data science leaders and, together with its industrial partners, will accelerate the development and application of pioneering data intensive science techniques that promise to offer great benefits to the UK and global economy and to enrich the STFC science programme.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>About the Centre</strong></div><div>Astrophysics, High Energy Physics and other Physical sciences are undergoing an \\u2018industrial revolution\\u2019 with huge data sets and complex models to describe them. For example, galaxy surveys, in which UCL is involved, will catalogue over the coming decade billions of galaxies. Similarly, Particle Physics experiments generate gigantic data sets.</div><div>The PhD studentships will be for four years. 'The CDT will prepare the next generation of scientists for both the data intensive challenges through dedicated training, a research project on a world-leading large-scale facility and a placements of six months in appropriate private, public or research organizations utilizing data intensive techniques. We have already engaged over 25 industry partners in the programme. Our aspiration is that this will lead to academia-industry cross-fertilization and to breakthroughs in DIS methods and applications. DIS is a fast moving field, and we expect the courses to evolve accordingly in coming years.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Training and Research in the Centre</strong></div><div>In their first year, students will benefit from a 150 hours of advanced training in data intensive science techniques, including a module on Machine Learning Techniques and an Industry Group Project, focusing on real-world DIS projects overseen by our Partners. This will be followed by the main thesis research project on a world-leading DIS experiment, with many students able to undertake a year-long placement at their experiment, for instance at CERN or Fermilab for the HEP stream.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Industry Placements</strong></div><div>All students will undertake a 6-month placement project, entirely separate from their PhD project, at one of our 25 industry partners, which will provide them opportunity to learn about the tools, techniques, datasets and challenges present in industry. As well as furthering the student's training, it will also allow them to use their training to solve real-world problems and promote knowledge-transfer between academia and industry.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>How to Apply</strong></div><div>We will be looking for candidates with an outstanding academic record (first-class or upper-second class honours primarily in Physics but we also welcome applications from Engineering, Computer Science or closely related subjects at UK undergraduate Masters level or equivalent) coupled with a broad outlook and a strong interest in Data Intensive Science. We particular encourage applications from female students &amp; students of ethnic minority backgrounds as these are currently underrepresented within the Physics industry.</div><div>Applicants should state in their application whether they are interested in a DIS research topic in Astrophysics, Particle Physics or another related DIS field. Inquiries can be addressed to the Centre\\u2019s PhD Admissions Team at <a href=\\\"mailto:dis-cdt-phd-admissions@live.ucl.ac.uk\\\">dis-cdt-phd-admissions@live.ucl.ac.uk</a>.</div><div><br></div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"University Coll. London\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/903311\"}},{\"value\":\"UCL Centre for Doctoral Training in Data Intensive Science\"}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-25\",\"control_number\":1763203,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Prof. Nikos Konstantinidis\",\"email\":\"n.konstantinidis@ucl.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\",\"astro-ph\",\"hep-ph\",\"physics\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"n.konstantinidis@ucl.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-4140-6360\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T09:02:10.103567\",\"internal_uid\":57971,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-07T11:24:54.878145+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763093,\"created\":\"2019-11-06T01:21:38.010600+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"cb7a8da3-574d-481e-bd82-9ea7199af467\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Research Associate in Particle Phenomenology\",\"description\":\"<div>THE DEPARTMENT</div><div><br></div><div>The Department of Physics at Durham University is one of the leading UK Physics departments with an outstanding reputation for excellence in teaching, research and employability of our students.&nbsp;</div><div>The Department is committed to advancing equality and we aim to ensure that our culture is inclusive, and that our systems support flexible and family-friendly working, as recognised by our Juno Champion and Athena SWAN Silver awards. We recognise and value the benefits of diversity throughout our staff and students.</div><div><br></div><div>THE ROLE</div><div><br></div><div>The successful applicants will have excellent research records in any area of particle physics phenomenology including beyond the standard model physics, electroweak and Higgs physics, flavour physics, model building, Monte Carlo simulations, precision standard model physics, neutrino physics, particle astrophysics and strong interactions. They will have an important role to play in the maintaining research excellence of the Institute. Applications from candidates with a strong record of engagement with experimental groups are encouraged. Candidates must contribute to fostering a collegial environment, as well as demonstrating their commitment to equality, diversity and inclusion. It is essential that the successful candidates will have a PhD in theoretical particle physics or closely related field, and will have demonstrated strength in independent research in theoretical particle physics appropriate to their experience. The candidate will also have good interpersonal and communication skills, and be able to work effectively with people at all levels of seniority and of different nationalities.</div><div><br></div><div>RESPONSIBILITIES</div><div><br></div><div>\\u2022\\tTo understand and convey material of a specialist or highly technical nature to the team or group of people through presentations and discussions that leads to the presentation of research papers in conferences and publications.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo prepare and deliver presentations on research outputs/activities to audiences which may include: research sponsors, academic and non-academic audiences.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo publish high quality outputs, including papers for submission to peer reviewed journals and papers for presentation at conferences and workshops under the direction of the Principal Investigator or Grant-holder.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo assist with the development of research objectives and proposals.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo conduct individual and collaborative research projects under the direction of the Principal Investigator or Grant-holder.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo work with the Principal Investigator or Grant-holder and other colleagues in the research group, as appropriate, to identify areas for research, develop new research methods and extend the research portfolio.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo deal with problems that may affect the achievement of research objectives and deadlines by discussing with the Principal Investigator or Grant-holder and offering creative or innovative solutions.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo liaise with research colleagues and make internal and external contacts to develop knowledge and understanding to form relationships for future research collaboration.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo plan and manage own research activity, research resources in collaboration with others and contribute to the planning of research projects.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo deliver training in research techniques/approaches to peers, visitors and students as appropriate.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo be involved in student supervision, as appropriate, and assist with the assessment of the knowledge of students.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo contribute to fostering a collegial working environment which is inclusive and welcoming and where everyone is treated fairly with dignity and respect.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo engage in citizenship to support the department and wider discipline.</div><div>\\u2022\\tTo engage in continuing professional development by participation in the undergraduate or postgraduate teaching programmes or by membership of departmental committees, etc. and by attending relevant training and development courses.&nbsp;</div><div>The post-holder is employed to work on research/a research project which will be led by another colleague. Whilst this means that the post-holder will not be carrying out independent research in his/her own right, the expectation is that they will contribute to the advancement of the project, through the development of their own research ideas/adaptation and development of research protocols.</div><div>Successful applicants will ideally be in post by 1st October 2020.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>THE REQUIREMENTS</div><div><br></div><div>Essential:</div><div>1. Qualifications</div><div>\\u2022 A good first degree in a relevant area of Physics or Mathematics.</div><div>\\u2022 A PhD (or be close to submission) in Physics or a related subject.</div><div>2. Experience \\u2022 Experience in conducting high quality academic research.</div><div>\\u2022 Demonstrable ability to write material of a quality commensurate with publication in highly ranked journals.</div><div>\\u2022 Demonstrable ability to present research papers at international conferences and communicate complex information to specialists and within the wider academic community.</div><div>3. Skills</div><div>\\u2022 Demonstrable ability to work cooperatively as part of a team, including participating in research meetings.</div><div>\\u2022 Ability to work independently on own initiative and to strict deadlines.</div><div>\\u2022 Excellent interpersonal and communication skills.</div><div>\\u2022 A good strategic fit with existing research expertise in Institute.</div><div><br></div><div>Desirable:</div><div>4. Experience</div><div>\\u2022 Strong publication record in peer-reviewed journals, commensurate with stage of career.</div><div>\\u2022 A track-record of presenting research at conferences, symposia, or meetings, commensurate with stage of career.</div><div>\\u2022 Demonstrable ability to develop research proposals and designs in collaboration with other academics.</div><div>\\u2022 Experience of overseeing students with respect to the development of their practical/research skills e.g. acting as a demonstrator; supervising student projects/practicals.</div><div>5.\\tSkills</div><div>\\u2022\\tDemonstrable ability to plan and manage independent research.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>HOW TO APPLY</div><div>For informal enquiries please contact Professor Michael Spannowsky, michael.spannowsky@durham.ac.uk. All enquiries will be treated in the strictest confidence.&nbsp;</div><div>Applications are particularly welcome from women and black and minority ethnic candidates, who are under-represented in academic posts in the University.</div><div><br></div><div><a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo?apply-982-15003\\\"><strong>Submit</strong></a><strong>&nbsp;the following items online at this website to complete your application:</strong></div><ul><li>Cover Letter&nbsp;</li><li>Curriculum Vitae&nbsp;</li><li>Research Statement&nbsp;</li><li>Publication List(s) (optional)&nbsp;</li><li>Two to Five Reference Letters&nbsp;(to be submitted online by the reference writers at this site)</li></ul><div><br></div><div>NEXT STEPS</div><div>The assessment for the post will include examination of submitted paperwork. Shortlisted candidates will be invited for Skype interview and assessment in January 2020.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Durham U., IPPP\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/908399\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-01-07\",\"control_number\":1763093,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Michael Spannowsky\",\"email\":\"michael.spannowsky@durham.ac.uk\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ph\",\"hep-th\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"michael.spannowsky@durham.ac.uk\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-8362-0576\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-06T01:21:37.909095\",\"internal_uid\":65634,\"submission_number\":\"None\"}},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T15:51:14.989586+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763092,\"created\":\"2019-11-05T23:55:01.511469+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15387\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"7399d9c0-a104-4dad-a710-bc5bbe3990b8\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Project Scientist in LBNL ATLAS Group\",\"description\":\"<div>This Project Scientist position will be focused on the construction and testing of ATLAS ITk Silicon Strip Modules for the ATLAS Experiment at HL-LHC. Please find additional information, and apply through, the Academic Jobs Online (AJO) posting: </div><div><br></div><div>      <a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15387\\\">https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15387</a></div><div><br></div><div>The application materials required are:</div><div>  Statement of Interest</div><div>  Curriculum Vitae</div><div>  Reference Letters: arrange to have at least three letters of reference submitted online by the reference writers through the AJO website.</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"LBNL, Berkeley\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/1189711\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-13\",\"control_number\":1763092,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Kevin Einsweiler\",\"email\":\"einsweiler@lbl.gov\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"reference_letters\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo/jobs/15387\"}]},\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"einsweiler@lbl.gov\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0002-4391-9100\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-05T23:55:01.334268\",\"internal_uid\":65633,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15387\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T15:48:19.642117+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763034,\"created\":\"2019-11-05T21:02:30.518618+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://stonybrooku.taleo.net/careersection/2/jobdetail.ftl?job=1903762&tz=GMT-04%3A00&tzname=America%2FNew_York\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"8884d499-54bf-4e20-ba08-9b8cc6ac6a13\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"T2K and DUNE\",\"description\":\"<div>A Postdoctoral Associate is sought to take a major role in the Stony Brook Neutrino and Nucleon Decay Group research program. The group plays a leading role in the SuperKamiokande, T2K and DUNE experiments.</div><div><br></div><div>The selected candidate will be responsible for the following:</div><div>&nbsp;</div><ul><li>Hardware/Software preparation for the T2K upgrade.</li><li>Development of the DUNE near detector design.</li><li>Experimental operations needed for T2K data collection.&nbsp;</li><li>T2K Hardware maintenance and calibration for T2K.</li></ul>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Stony Brook U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/1228041\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2019-12-01\",\"control_number\":1763034,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Clark McGrew\",\"email\":\"clark.mcgrew@stonybrook.edu\"},{\"name\":\"Chang Kee Jung\",\"email\":\"alpinist@nngroup.physics.sunysb.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-ex\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"clark.mcgrew@stonybrook.edu\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0003-2053-3739\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-05T21:02:30.391907\",\"internal_uid\":65629,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"Postdoctoral Associate - 1903762\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-06T16:09:13.127837+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763033,\"created\":\"2019-11-05T17:10:41.239432+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"http://www.theophys.kth.se/~egor/\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"0396210b-da38-4809-8980-844d532d2e94\",\"regions\":[\"Europe\"],\"position\":\"Theoretical Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>Egor Babaev's group at the Royal Institute of Technology invites applications for several anticipated postdoctoral research associate positions. A Ph.D. in Physics is required. Candidates with a solid publication record and background in theoretical condensed matter, high energy, computational or mathematical physics (in particular superconductivity, magnetism, statistical mechanics and critical phenomena, ultra cold atoms, physics of glasses , topological defects and solitons, Monte-Carlo simulations are especially encouraged to apply. The description of our research topics is available at: <a href=\\\"http://www.theophys.kth.se/~egor/\\\">www.theophys.kth.se/~egor/</a> We are committed in our efforts to hire candidates who will enhance the gender balance. We strongly encourage women to apply. The review of applications will begin immediately and will continues until the anticipated position is filled.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Application Materials Required:</strong></div><div><a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo?apply-1740-15356-1\\\"><strong>Submit</strong></a><strong>&nbsp;the following items online at this website to complete your application:</strong></div><ul><li>Cover Letter</li><li>Curriculum Vitae</li><li>Research Statement</li><li>Publication List</li><li>Three Reference Letters&nbsp;(to be submitted online by the reference writers at this site&nbsp;</li><li>)</li></ul><div><strong>And anything else requested in the position description.</strong></div><div><br></div><div><strong>Further Info:</strong><a href=\\\"http://www.theophys.kth.se/~egor/\\\">www.theophys.kth.se/~egor/</a></div><div><br></div><div>46012345678</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Theoretical Physics KTH</div><div>AlbaNova University Center</div><div>10691</div><div>Stockholm</div><div>Sweden</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Royal Inst. Tech., Stockholm\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/903171\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-02-05\",\"control_number\":1763033,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Babaev, Egor\",\"email\":\"babaevegor@gmail.com\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/authors/1017766\"}}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"hep-th\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"sammy1@fnal.gov\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-5928-8131\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-05T17:10:41.011614\",\"internal_uid\":64849,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15356\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-05T17:10:41.239439+00:00\"},{\"links\":{},\"id\":1763032,\"created\":\"2019-11-05T17:02:44.414753+00:00\",\"metadata\":{\"urls\":[{\"value\":\"https://www.niu.edu/physics/pages/reu.shtml\"}],\"ranks\":[\"POSTDOC\"],\"status\":\"open\",\"$schema\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/schemas/records/jobs.json\",\"_bucket\":\"c125d23b-f54c-4172-a208-f9f96b77359c\",\"regions\":[\"North America\"],\"position\":\"Physics\",\"description\":\"<div>This 8-week program will provide novel research experiences for undergraduates and K-12 science teachers. Research opportunities span a broad range of physics, including high-energy and intensity-frontier particle physics, beam and accelerator physics and condensed matter and materials physics.</div><div><br></div><div>Matched with an NIU faculty mentor, participants will gain vital research skills and visit both nearby Fermilab and Argonne National Laboratories. Activities will also include workshops on scientific communication, lab safety, responsible conduct in research and participation in a campus-wide student poster session at the end of the program.</div><div><br></div><div>Applications received by February 2, 2020 receive full consideration. Applications received after that date may be considered if space allows.</div><div><br></div><div>Primary selection criteria include academic record (via uploaded transcripts), career objectives (via a personal statement) and at least two letters of recommendation. Note that it is the responsibility of applicants to ensure that reference letters are received in a timely manner. Unofficial transcripts are acceptable. The personal statement should be a short essay (\\u2264~ 4000 characters) detailing your previous research experiences (if any) and personal and professional goals, and how you believe this program in particular would assist you in attaining those goals. It would be helpful to mention any skills that you have that might aid you in your research, including, but not limited to, computer and programming proficiency, laboratory techniques, a strong math background and personal skills.</div><div><br></div><div>Selected participants in the REU (RET) program will receive a $4000 ($6000) stipend, free housing and a food allowance.</div><div><br></div><div><strong>Application Materials Required:</strong></div><div><a href=\\\"https://academicjobsonline.org/ajo?apply-1565-15366\\\"><strong>Submit</strong></a><strong>&nbsp;the following items online at this website to complete your application:</strong></div><ul><li>Personal statement</li><li>Transcript(s)</li><li>Any additional material(s) (optional)</li><li>Two or More Reference Letters&nbsp;(to be submitted online by the reference writers at this site&nbsp;</li><li>)</li></ul><div><strong>And anything else requested in the description.</strong></div><div><br></div><div><strong>Further Info:</strong><a href=\\\"https://www.niu.edu/physics/pages/reu.shtml%3Cbr%3E\\\">https://www.niu.edu/physics/pages/reu.shtml</a></div><div><a href=\\\"https://www.niu.edu/physics/pages/ret.shtml\\\">https://www.niu.edu/physics/pages/ret.shtml</a></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Department of Physics</div><div>Northern Illinois University</div><div>DeKalb, IL 60115</div>\",\"_collections\":[\"Jobs\"],\"institutions\":[{\"value\":\"Northern Illinois U.\",\"record\":{\"$ref\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/institutions/903082\"}}],\"deadline_date\":\"2020-02-02\",\"control_number\":1763032,\"contact_details\":[{\"name\":\"Adelman, Jahred\",\"email\":\"jahred.adelman@niu.edu\"}],\"arxiv_categories\":[\"physics\"],\"acquisition_source\":{\"email\":\"sammy1@fnal.gov\",\"orcid\":\"0000-0001-5928-8131\",\"method\":\"submitter\",\"source\":\"submitter\",\"datetime\":\"2019-11-05T17:02:44.304068\",\"internal_uid\":64849,\"submission_number\":\"None\"},\"external_job_identifier\":\"AJO-15366\"},\"updated\":\"2019-11-05T17:02:44.414758+00:00\"}],\"total\":889},\"links\":{\"self\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/jobs/?page=1&sort=mostrecent&q=&size=25\",\"next\":\"https://labs.inspirehep.net/api/jobs/?page=2&sort=mostrecent&q=&size=25\"},\"sort_options\":[{\"value\":\"mostrecent\",\"display\":\"Most Recent\"}]}"
